# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abortion-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] The **1976 Republican National Convention** was a United States political convention of the Republican Party that met from August 16 to August 19, 1976, to select the party's nominees for President of the United States and vice president.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Held in Kemper Arena in Kansas City, Missouri, the Republican National Convention nominated President Gerald Ford for a full term, but only after narrowly defeating a strong challenge from former governor of California Ronald Reagan.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Senator Bob Dole from Kansas for vice president over incumbent Vice President Nelson Rockefeller, who did not seek nomination for a full term.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] The keynote address was delivered by Howard Baker, then a U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Other notable speakers included Minnesota Representative Al Quie, retired Lieutenant Colonel and former Vietnam War prisoner of war Raymond Schrump, former Democratic Texas Governor John Connally, Providence, Rhode Island mayor Vincent Cianci, and Michigan Senator Robert P.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] It was the last national convention by either of the two major parties to feature a seriously contested nomination between candidates.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Kansas City, Missouri had not hosted a major party convention since the 1928 Republican National Convention that nominated Herbert Hoover.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Its premier venue, Kemper Arena, was diminutive by national standards but it was new, and the city aggressively courted the convention planners of both parties.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] The Democrats demurred early on, citing a lack of hotel accommodations, but Republicans were more receptive because the city had a reliably enthusiastic base of the party, and "fit the Midwestern image of Jerry Ford".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Going into the convention, Ford had won more primary delegates than Reagan, and also won a plurality in the popular vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] However, Ford did not have enough delegates to secure the nomination (1,130 delegates were needed to win the presidential nomination), and as the convention opened both candidates were seen as still having a chance to win.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Because of this, both Ford and Reagan arrived in Kansas City before the convention opened to woo the remaining uncommitted delegates in an effort to secure the nomination.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Reagan benefited from his highly committed delegates, notably "Reagan's Raiders" of the Texas delegation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] They and other conservative Western and Southern delegates particularly faulted the Ford Administration's foreign policy of détente towards the Soviet Union, criticizing his signing of the Helsinki Accords and indirectly blaming him for the April 1975 Fall of Saigon.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] The pro-Reagan Texas delegates worked hard to persuade delegates from other states to support Reagan.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Ford, meanwhile, used all of the perks and patronage of the presidency to win over wavering delegates, including trips aboard Air Force One and personal meetings with Ford himself.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] White House Chief of Staff Dick Cheney proved to be an important figure in working to build support among those state delegations on the fence between Ford and Reagan, including the Mississippi delegation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] White House political advisor Harry Dent also played a central role in helping President Ford work with the state delegations, who met with Ford and his aides in a presidential office set up on-site at the convention in Kansas City.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Headlines during the Republican convention in Kansas City hinted at the still-simmering debates within the rank-and-file of the Republicans as to whether or not a new party might be formed out of the weaknesses of the Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Newspaper headlines also told the story of the uncommitted delegates whose "wavering" at the convention made them the focus of both the Ford and the Reagan camps.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] "New 'Stars' Stealing GOP Show," The Chicago Tribune's Wednesday, August 18, 1976, headlines told readers.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Estimates ranged from 93 to as many as 115 delegates uncommitted at the time of the convention.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] The largest block of uncommitted delegates were from Mississippi and another block were from Illinois's delegation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Wednesday, August 18, 1976, saw the uncommitted delegates break on the 1st ballot for President Gerald Ford, who won the nomination on the 1st roll call of delegates by a vote of 1,187-1,070.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Reagan had promised, if nominated, to name Senator Richard Schweiker of Pennsylvania as his running mate, in a bid to attract liberals and centrists in the party.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] This move backfired, however, as many conservatives (such as North Carolina Senator Jesse Helms) were infuriated by Reagan's choice of the "liberal" Schweiker, while few moderate delegates switched to Reagan.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Helms promptly began a movement to draft Conservative Senator James L.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Buckley of New York as the presidential nominee.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] The key vote of the convention occurred when Reagan's managers proposed a rules change that would have required Ford to publicly announce his running mate before the presidential balloting.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Reagan's managers hoped that when Ford announced his choice for vice president, it would anger one of the two factions of the party and thus help Reagan.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Ford's supporters derisively described the proposed rules change as the "misery loves company" amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] The proposed rules change was defeated by a vote of 1180 to 1069, and Ford gained the momentum he needed to win the presidential nomination.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] The balloting was still close, however, as Ford won with 1187 votes to 1070 votes for Reagan (and one for Elliot Richardson of Massachusetts).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Conservatives succeeded in inserting several key planks into the party platform, some of which were implicitly critical of the President's own policies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Reagan and Senator Jesse Helms successfully had a "moral foreign policy" plank inserted.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Wade* decision, the 1976 Republican platform became the first to advocate a Human Life Amendment to the Constitution, despite the fact that *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Wade* had been a 7–2 decision, and 5 of the 7 (Burger, Stewart, Brennan, Blackmun, and Powell) had been appointed to the Supreme Court by Republican presidents.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Dole as his running mate, as unelected incumbent Vice President Rockefeller had announced the previous fall that he would not be a candidate for a full term in 1976.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] After Ronald Reagan lost the presidential ballot to incumbent Gerald Ford, 103 of his delegates walked out of the convention, and the remainder decided to scatter their votes among 30 people.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Bob Dole prevailed by an overwhelming margin.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] There was no scheduled time slot for the runner-up to deliver a formal concession speech; however, when Ford and Reagan met on the dais after Ford's acceptance speech, the president insisted that the former governor accompany him to the podium to deliver a few remarks.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Reagan gave an eloquent and stirring speech that overshadowed Ford's own acceptance address, despite being little more than five minutes long.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Some delegates later stated that they left the convention wondering if they had voted for the wrong candidate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] A contemporary media account stated that if a motion to reconsider the nomination had been in order, it might have passed.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Ford and Dole went on to lose to Jimmy Carter and Walter Mondale in the 1976 election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Reagan defeated Carter in the 1980 election to become president, and won again in 1984, beating Democratic challenger Mondale.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/1976-republican-national-convention] Dole ran for president in 1980, 1988, and 1996, gaining the nomination the last time, but losing to Bill Clinton by a large margin.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The proposition was placed on the ballot as a result of a joint effort by California's leading Democrats: Governor Gavin Newsom, Senate President pro tempore Toni Atkins, and Assembly Speaker Anthony Rendon.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The constitutional amendment passed the California State Senate in a 29–8 vote on June 20, 2022, and the California State Assembly with a 58–17 vote on June 27 – ahead of a June 30 deadline to have the amendment voted on in November.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Polling on Proposition 1 consistently showed that two-thirds to three-quarters of California voters supported the proposition, and suggested that the ballot measure would pass by a wide margin.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The ballot measure derived most of its support from the California Democratic Party, feminists, medical professional organizations, labor unions, and newspaper editorial boards.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Some supporters said the amendment would codify existing law, and protect Californian women from restrictive abortion policies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Opposition to Proposition 1 came from the California Republican Party, some Christian organizations, and anti-abortion groups.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Part of the opposition argued that the ballot measure would legalize late-term abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Any amendment to the Constitution of California requires the passage of a California ballot proposition by a simple majority of the voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] A constitutional amendment may be placed on the ballot by either a two-thirds vote in the California State Legislature, or though an initiative attaining signatures equal to eight percent of the votes cast in the last gubernatorial election through the exercise of the initiative power by the voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In the first session of the California State Legislature in 1850, the legislature passed the Crimes and Punishments Act, which criminalized an abortion in all circumstances except to save a woman's life.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The State Legislature amended California's abortion law in 1967 with the Therapeutic Abortion Act, signed by Governor Ronald Reagan in June, which extended the right to an abortion in cases of rape and incest up to 20 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In 1969, the California Supreme Court issued a ruling in *People v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Belous* that upheld the right to an abortion and struck down section 274 of the California Penal Code, which had defined the punishment for people who provided, supplied, or administered an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The state voted in 1972 to pass Proposition 11, which amended the state constitution to include a right to privacy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Through Proposition 11, the California Supreme Court ruled in *Committee to Defend Reproductive Rights v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Myers* in 1981 that the constitutionally protected right to privacy included the right to choose whether to have an abortion, preventing Medi-Cal from restricting abortion coverage.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In September 1987, Governor George Deukmejian signed Assembly Bill 2274, which required unemancipated minors have parental consent before receiving an abortion, providing an exception for medical emergencies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The parental consent law was upheld in 1996 in a 4–3 ruling by the California Supreme Court in *American Academy of Pediatrics v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Lungren*, with the majority stating that the constitutional right to privacy did not extend to minors due to them not having the same rights as adults.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The following year, the case was reheard after two members of the 1996 majority decision retired and were succeeded by Governor Pete Wilson's appointees.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The law was found unconstitutional, with the California Supreme Court ruling that AB 2274 violated the right to privacy in the state constitution.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In 2002, Governor Gray Davis signed the Reproductive Privacy Act, which legalized abortion up to fetal viability, whereafter abortions can only be performed if continued pregnancy poses a risk to the woman's life.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The law was struck down as unconstitutional in a 5–4 ruling in 2018 by the United States Supreme Court in *National Institute of Family and Life Advocates v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Becerra*, finding that the FACT Act violated the First Amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In 2019, Governor Gavin Newsom signed the College Student Right to Access Act, which required public universities to provide abortion medication on campus from January 2023, the first law of its kind in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Newsom's predecessor, Brown, vetoed a similar bill in 2018.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In the 2021–22 session of the State Legislature, 16 bills were introduced in either the Assembly or the Senate to improve abortion access and legal protections in the state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Before Senate Constitutional Amendment 10 passed the legislature, two of the bills had been signed into law by Newsom, eliminating out-of-pocket expenses for abortions and protecting Californians from civil liability cases in states with contradictory abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] California's move to strengthen abortion rights was part of a broader effort throughout the United States in anticipation of the United States Supreme Court case *Dobbs v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, which would potentially result in the court overturning or weakening *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The legislation and actions taken by Newsom represent California's intention to become a sanctuary state for abortion rights, a term previously used in reference to the state's response to immigration.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] By the end of the session on August 31, the State Legislature passed an additional series of legislation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Other legislation imposed limitations on the sharing of medical records and ended the requirement for coroners to investigate self-induced or criminal abortions or allow prosecution or civil action against people based on a fetal death certificate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] After vetoing AB 2320 on September 22, Newsom signed 13 of the bills into law on September 27.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In 2005, 2006, and 2008, there were three initiatives – Proposition 73, Proposition 85, and Proposition 4 respectively – that would have established parental notification and a mandatory waiting period on abortions in California.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] All three proposals were rejected by the voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Proposition 73 caused concern for its opponents by defining abortion as the "death of the unborn child" instead of using clinical terms such as fetus or embryo.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] When Proposition 85 was placed on the ballot in 2006, the proposed constitutional amendment instead defined abortion as "the use of any means to terminate the pregnancy".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The parental notification initiative underwent another revision before appearing on the 2008 ballot, allowing doctors to notify an adult family member other than the parent if the latter was abusive.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The three-time effort to establish a parental notification law in California was largely funded by *San Diego Reader* owner Jim Holman and winemaker Don Sebastiani.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] 2008 marked the last time California voters decided on an abortion-related proposition.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On May 2, 2022, *Politico* published a leaked draft opinion of *Dobbs*, which showed the Supreme Court overturning *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Casey* and determining that the federal constitution did not grant a right to an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In response to the draft opinion, Newsom, Senate President pro tempore Toni Atkins, and Assembly Speaker Anthony Rendon issued a joint statement of their intent to enshrine abortion rights in the state constitution through an amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 24, the Supreme Court overturned *Roe* and *Casey*, with the final opinion being largely similar to the leaked draft opinion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Due to the Supreme Court decision and abortion bans in other states, California experienced an increase of patients seeking abortions, with Planned Parenthood saying that the majority of new patients came from Texas.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Just weeks after *Roe*'s reversal, Planned Parenthood experienced an 847% increase in Arizona patients, with most out-of-state patients traveling along Interstate 8 in Southern California and lengthening wait times at a Planned Parenthood clinic in El Centro.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] With abortion banned in Arizona, some of the state's abortion providers stated their plans on opening clinics on the western side of the state border in California.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] According to the Guttmacher Institute, the number of patients seeking abortions in California could increase from 46,000 to 1.4 million on an annual basis.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The UCLA School of Law Center on Reproductive Health, Law, and Policy made a more conservative estimate, approximating that 10,600 more people will come to California for abortion services each year.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] California was one of six US states that voted on an abortion-related ballot measure in 2022, the most to occur in the US in a single year, with votes also occurring in Kansas, Kentucky, Michigan, Montana, and Vermont.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Of the six, three – California, Michigan, and Vermont – asked voters to enshrine the right to an abortion in their respective state constitutions, while the other states worked to implement restrictive abortion policies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On August 2, Kansas voters rejected a proposed constitutional amendment that would have stated that the state constitution did not grant the right to an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On September 8, the Michigan Supreme Court ordered the Board of State Canvassers to certify the initiative and place it on the ballot in a 5–2 decision, which the board did the next day on September 9.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 8, 2022, Atkins introduced Senate Constitutional Amendment 10 (SCA 10), co-authored by Rendon and other state Democrats to codify a constitutional right to reproductive freedom.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Atkins stated that SCA 10 would codify abortion and contraception protections that already existed in California state law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] For the constitutional amendment to appear on the November 2022 ballot, it had to receive a two-thirds vote in both houses of the legislature by June 30.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] SCA 10 moved through the legislative process at an unusually fast pace.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 14, SCA 10 passed in a 9–1 vote in the Senate Judiciary Committee, with the lone opposition vote coming from a Republican.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The proposed amendment also passed the Senate Elections and Amendments Committee in a 3–1 vote on the same day.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 16, SCA 10 passed 5–2 in the Senate Appropriations Committee.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] After having cleared the committees the amendment was assigned to, the Senate voted 29–8 on June 20 to pass SCA 10, which occurred along party lines.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Democratic senators Bob Archuleta and Bob Wieckowski and Republican senator Andreas Borgeas did not record a vote on the amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 29, the Senate voted 28–8 to pass Senate Bill 131, which required the California Secretary of State to designate SCA 10 as Proposition 1 on the ballot of the upcoming election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 23, the Assembly Judiciary Committee passed the amendment in a 7–2 vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 27, the Assembly voted 58–17 to pass SCA 10, allowing the amendment to be put to a vote before California voters in the general election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] During the Assembly debate, Republican assemblymember Kevin Kiley asked whether the constitutional amendment would change limitations on abortion past viability.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] After a 30 second pause, Rendon quietly spoke with other Democratic assemblymembers and asked for the question to be restated, thereafter promising to answer Kiley's question another time.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 29, the Assembly passed SB 131 in a 60–17 vote, sending the bill to the governor, who approved the legislation the next day, making certain SCA 10's designation as Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On July 1, 2022, California Secretary of State Shirley Weber designated SCA 10 as Proposition 1 for the November 2022 election, being one of seven ballot propositions in the general election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The constitutional amendment's designation as Proposition 1 was pursuant to the requirement in SB 131.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Proposition 1 was later given the ballot title "Constitutional Right to Reproductive Freedom" by July 8.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] For the voter information guide provided by the Secretary of State, the Legislative Analyst's Office (LAO) did not find that Proposition 1 had any fiscal effect, unless a court interpreted the proposition as expanding reproductive rights beyond existing law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The official argument in favor of Proposition 1 was co-written by Shannon Udovic-Constant, Jodi Hicks, and Carol Moon Goldberg, each representing the California Medical Association, the Planned Parenthood Affiliates of California, and the League of Women Voters of California respectively.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In their argument, they wrote, in part, that "a person's right to an abortion or contraceptives should be protected in California".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Michele Goodwin, a professor at the University of California, Irvine, said the amendment would give legal opportunities to people who are denied contraceptives.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On June 24, *San Francisco Chronicle*'s Sophia Bollag found that Republican candidates campaigning for statewide office in California were largely quiet about abortion rights and the effort to codify those rights into the state constitution.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] If Proposition 1 removes the viability limit, California would become the seventh state to have no such limit, joining Alaska, Colorado, New Jersey, New Mexico, Oregon, and Vermont along with Washington, D.C. in that regard.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] UC Berkeley law school dean Erwin Chemerinsky argued that Proposition 1 would not change the existing state law on viability, "Rights are not absolute even if enumerated.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] US President Joe Biden and his strategists watched Proposition 1 and initiatives in other states to craft a national strategy to protect abortion rights as voters had done in Kansas, where the Democratic National Committee conducted digital canvassing to get out the vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Hicks acknowledged that the short time frame in which Proposition 1 was put on the ballot presented a challenge to voter awareness and turnout since ballot measure planning typically starts years in advance, not months.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Some of the commentary on Proposition 1 centered on its effectiveness if the federal government imposes a national abortion ban.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] David Lightman and Lindsey Holden wrote an article in *The Sacramento Bee* on July 18 that the ballot proposition and the wider issue of abortion could lead to the return of nullification policies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Carillo, told *Politico* that "[a] state constitutional right allows California's lawyers to position state sovereignty against federal commerce clause powers." *The Sacramento Bee*'s Andrew Sheeler noted, "The Supremacy Clause of the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Chemerinsky said, "If Congress adopts a law prohibiting abortions (like Lindsey Graham's), that would pre-empt state laws to the contrary," such as Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Raich* would give Congress the standing to regulate abortion on commerce grounds, "I think abortion is economic activity... because it is a service bought and sold." Conversely, Chemerinsky said any federal law that guaranteed abortion rights would supersede any conflicting law at the state level.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] San José State University and Menlo College lecturer Donna Crane told the Associated Press that a federal ban or subsequent decisions by the Supreme Court would render California's abortion laws null.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In early August, neither supporters nor opponents of Proposition 1 had yet to spend any money on the proposed constitutional amendment compared to the six other propositions on the 2022 general election ballot in California, in which US$461 million had already been spent.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] By August 18, the Yes campaign raised $1.2 million while the No campaign received comparatively little financial support except for a $1000 contribution from Sacramento bishop Jaime Soto.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] White and Korte from *Politico* wrote that the proposition's opponents "are certain to be outspent." By September 17, the Yes campaign received $3.2 million in contributions, with about $130,000 in contributions going to the No campaign.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Comparatively, the campaigns for the other California ballot propositions spent $564.8 million by this time.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Data from the California Fair Political Practices Commission showed the Yes campaign's top donors as of September 13 were M.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The commission stated that the No campaign did not attain the reporting threshold necessary for the disclosure of its top donors.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On September 15, the Federated Indians of Graton Rancheria pledged $5 million to the Yes campaign, representing the campaign's largest contribution to date.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Steve and Connie Ballmer, the former being the owner of the Los Angeles Clippers and former CEO of Microsoft, each made $250,000 late September donations in support of Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] By late September, Garofoli stated that the Yes campaign had enough money for a week's worth of television advertisements, and the No campaign only raised enough money for yard signs in Temecula.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In October, Newsom spent $2.5 million for a television advertisement, which debuted on October 10, promoting Proposition 1 and urging Californians to vote for the constitutional amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The spending for the advertisement made Newsom the second-largest contributor to the Yes campaign, second only to the Federated Indians of Graton Rancheria.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On October 12, the Yes campaign announced the beginning of its media campaign in multiple formats and languages.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In mid-October, 2022 Los Angeles mayoral candidate Rick Caruso donated $100,000 to the Yes campaign's committee.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] The donation came months after a May 3 pledge Caruso made on Twitter to donate an initial $100,000 and, ultimately, $1 million toward the constitutional amendment's passage.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] By late October, data showed that the Yes campaign spent $14 million, and the No campaign spent $1.6 million, with $681.4 million spent in other California proposition campaigns.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] By the end of the campaign, the Yes campaign raised 10 times as much money compared to the No campaign, raising $22 million against the No campaign's $2.2 million.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] KQED-FM held a podcast session on September 29 in which a panel discussed Proposition 1 as part of Prop Fest 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On October 8, CalMatters' Emily Hoeven and David Lesher discussed Proposition 1 and the other ballot propositions at Politifest, an event organized by *Voice of San Diego* at the University of San Diego.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] In San Francisco, former United States Secretary of State Hillary Clinton moderated an October 13 panel discussion on Proposition 1 involving Lieutenant Governor Eleni Kounalakis, NARAL Pro-Choice America president Mini Timmaraju, and Planned Parenthood Affiliates of California president Jodi Hicks.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] A factcheck from the Associated Press determined that the claim of Proposition 1 legalizing late-term abortion was "missing context" as there was no mention in the constitutional amendment and the courts were unlikely to interpret it as legalizing such abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] PolitiFact's Gabrielle Settles and *USA Today*'s Nate Trela reached the same conclusion in their factchecks of the claim.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On August 25, a Women's Equality Day event at San Francisco City Hall was interrupted while Supervisor Catherine Stefani was giving a speech by anti-abortion protesters demonstrating against Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] A number of protesters had traveled from as far as South Carolina.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] Competing protests over Proposition 1 occurred at Sather Gate on the University of California, Berkeley campus between Rise Up for Abortion Rights and Pro-Life San Francisco on August 26, raising awareness of the proposed constitutional amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p01] On October 8, Women's March held 450 marches across the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] With the effort to codify reproductive rights into the state constitution being initiated by the California's Democratic political leadership – Newsom, Atkins, and Rendon – the Yes campaign for Proposition 1 received broad support from the California Democratic Party and its membership.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The campaign, led by Protect Abortion Rights, maintained a list of supporters that comprised the coalition in support of Proposition 1, and explained in the footer of their website that the campaign was largely supported by Atkins and the Planned Parenthood Affiliates of California.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] In that list, California's two US senators, seven US representatives, 15 state senators, and 24 state assemblymembers were part of the Yes campaign's coalition.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Dianne Feinstein and Alex Padilla, the state's US senators, officially joined the coalition on July 28.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Democratic candidates seeking elected office, such as state controller candidate Malia Cohen and state assemblymember candidate Diane Papan, also indicated their support for Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] State controller candidate Lanhee Chen gave qualified support for enshrining California's existing abortion law into the state constitution, and expressing concern about Proposition 1's language.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The decision to have an abortion belongs to the pregnant woman alone, no one else.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] That should have been spelled out." On September 9, the Peace and Freedom Party announced its support for Proposition 1 while criticizing the limited scope of the constitutional amending by stating, "It makes explicit the right to abortion and contraceptives in the California constitution.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] It does not include universal free health care, paid family leave, and child care, which would give us real reproductive freedom.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] But still, this is a YES." On October 11, the California National Party announced its support for voting Yes on Proposition 1, according to the positions stated in the party platform.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Local governments compose part of the Yes campaign.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Five county boards of supervisors voted unanimously to support amending the state constitution to protect reproductive rights: Alameda on May 10, San Mateo on August 2, Santa Clara on August 16, Humboldt on October 4 and Los Angeles on November 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On May 24, the San Diego County Board of Supervisors voted 3–1 to support a constitutional amendment for abortion rights, with the lone vote against being Republican Jim Desmond.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The Irvine City Council voted 3–2 on July 12 to support the constitutional amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On August 30, four members of the Oakland City Council announced a September 20 vote on a resolution declaring Oakland's support for Proposition 1, which the city council adopted in an 8–0 vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] In Los Angeles, city council president Nury Martinez and president pro tempore Mitch O'Farrell introduced a resolution on September 20 supporting the proposition.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The city council passed the resolution on October 25.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Urging Californians to vote Yes, the League of Women Voters of California wrote that "Prop 1 protects access to the care that will give individuals and families the freedom to make those choices".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The National Women's Political Caucus of California endorsed Proposition 1, stating that the constitutional amendment "will ensure robust protection for both California residents as well as anyone seeking abortions here".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The Women's Foundation California supports the constitutional amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Multiple medical professional organizations expressed their support for Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Essential Access Health, Planned Parenthood Affiliates of California, and Training in Early Abortion for Comprehensive Healthcare are co-sponsors for the Yes campaign.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On September 8, Planned Parenthood of Orange and San Bernardino Counties senior vice president Robert Armenta authored an opinion article in the *Los Angeles Times* in support of Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Several labor unions in California joined the Yes campaign.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The California Teachers Association board of directors endorsed Proposition 1, with CTA president E.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] NARAL Pro-Choice America president Mini Timmaraju expressed support for Proposition 1 and said that the constitutional amendment "sends a clear message across the country that California will never stop protecting the freedom to decide".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On August 3, Equality California expressed support for Proposition 1, calling it an "opportunity to further solidify California's long-time standing as a nationwide leader in reproductive rights".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On August 16, Asian Americans Advancing Justice Southern California announced its support for Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Courage California endorsed voting for Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Disability Rights California gave its support for Proposition 1 on September 30 on the basis that "[p]eople with disabilities and communities of color are disproportionately impacted by restrictions to contraceptives and abortions".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Sierra Club California's position on Proposition 1 is Yes, writing that "Sierra Club works to advance environmental and social justice, and support for Proposition 1 is consistent with those values".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] California Environmental Voters also endorsed Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On October 17, the Freedom From Religion Foundation announced their support for Proposition 1 "to make sure that religious ideologues cannot impose their will on California residents when it comes to reproductive health".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The San Francisco Bay Area Planning and Urban Research Association recommended voting Yes on Proposition 1, writing that "it is important that the state ensures the strength and clarity of reproductive freedom law".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The Bay Area Council represents one business group that joined the Yes campaign.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The group leading the campaign against Proposition 1 was California Together.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The California Republican Party announced its opposition to Proposition 1 on August 19.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The No campaign was supported by state senator Brian Dahle and assemblymembers Megan Dahle and Jim Patterson, the latter of whom co-wrote the official argument against Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] In San Mateo, Rod Linhares was the lone city council candidate who did not share their position on either abortion or Proposition 1, with all other candidates for the San Mateo City Council affirming their support for both.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On November 2, Linhares emailed the *San Mateo Daily Journal*'s Mark Simon, stating his opposition to Proposition 1 and claiming that the ballot measure "allows abortion in the last three months" of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The California Catholic Conference issued a statement opposing SCA 10, stating that the amendment would "legalize and protect abortion up to the point just prior to delivery" and calling for Catholics in the state to oppose the ballot measure.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The statement was signed by Los Angeles Archbishop José Horacio Gómez, San Francisco Archbishop Salvatore Cordileone, and bishops from 10 other California dioceses.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The California Family Council wrote that "Proposition 1 is an extreme and costly proposal that does nothing to advance women's health".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The American Council of Evangelicals and California Knights of Columbus also represent part of the No campaign.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Southern California News Group editorial board member John Seiler wrote an opinion article in *The San Bernardino Sun* on September 3 in which he stated that he would vote against Proposition 1, noting that the ballot measure will still pass.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The Libertarian Party of California published a voter guide that stated the party's position on candidates and ballot measures.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Sharing the party's position on all other state propositions, the Libertarian Party omitted its position on Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] *The Orange County Register*'s editorial board opted not to publish a position on Proposition 1, instead taking positions on the state's other ballot measures.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Along with all of the state's other propositions, the California branch of the Council on American–Islamic Relations claimed no position on Proposition 1, stating that "though the issues on the ballot are of great importance, they fall outside the scope of CAIR-CA's focus and mission".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] In a question and answer interview with *The San Diego Union-Tribune*, insurance commissioner candidate Robert Howell did not share his position on Proposition 1, writing in part, "I do not think the Insurance Commissioner's Office has any control of this issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On October 4, the San Marcos City Council voted 3–2 against a resolution affirming the city's support for Proposition 1 as the majority determined that the city should not take a position on the issue and let the voters decide its fate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Voting on Proposition 1 coincided with all other elections in California on November 8, 2022, with polls open from 7:00 am to 8:00 pm PST (UTC−8).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] All active registered voters in California were mailed a ballot ahead of the election, which began no later than October 10.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] For a ballot to be considered valid, it had to be returned and postmarked on or before November 8 and received by November 15.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The ballot could also have been delivered in-person at a ballot drop box, polling place, or county elections office by 8:00 pm on November 8.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Throughout California, there was at least one ballot drop box for every 15,000 registered voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Voters had the ability to track their ballots' status to ensure that they were received and counted.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The deadline for eligible voters to register online or by mail was 15 days before the election – October 24.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Eligible voters who registered after the October 24 deadline had to do so at a county elections office, polling place, or vote center to cast their vote in the election, but had until 8:00 pm on November 8 to do so.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Voters in 27 of the 58 counties had the option to vote early in person from October 29 to November 8.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] According to the California Voter Bill of Rights, people who were already in line by 8:00 pm to vote can cast one, even if it was past the deadline.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] California voters were able to receive information and assistance in 10 languages: English, Spanish, Chinese, Hindi, Japanese, Khmer, Korean, Tagalog, Thai and Vietnamese.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Several different tabulation systems were used in the election by the state's 58 counties, such as Dominion ImageCast, Hart Verity, and ES&S EVS.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Los Angeles County used its own publicly-owned system, VSAP, for tabulation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] For Proposition 1 to pass, it needed approval from a majority of the voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] By the time polls closed, about a third of the votes had already been counted from those cast in early voting and showed Yes votes outnumbering No about two votes to one.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On the night of the election, multiple news outlets called the results in favor of the Yes vote, with NBC News doing so at 8:40 pm PST, ABC News by 8:50 pm, and the Associated Press at 10:38 pm.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] CNN made the same projection at 2:18 am on November 9.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Secretary of State Shirley Weber certified the election on December 16, affirming the passage of Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] With the ballot measure passing, it entered into effect on December 21.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] The Yes vote won 49 out of 52 congressional districts, including nine that elected Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Democratic candidates across California wore pink on November 8 in support of Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Catherine Hadro, the No campaign's media relations director, issued a statement on the outcome, "The battle now shifts to the courts and the legislature.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] On the night of the election, the California Family Council held a vigil at the California State Capitol.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] 1 will inevitably be challenged in the courts".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Following Proposition 1's passage, the Guttmacher Institute reclassified California's abortion policy as "very protective", the second-highest level of protection categorized by Guttmacher.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Along with California, voters in Michigan and Vermont affirmed the right to an abortion in their state constitutions respectively with Proposal 3 and Proposal 5, becoming the first three states in the nation to do so.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] In Kentucky and Montana, the former's Amendment 2 and the latter's Legislative Referendum 131, which would have restricted abortion rights, were rejected by the two states' voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] As such, all five states voted to preserve abortion rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Let's put this to the people." The ACLU and the Fairness Project planned such measures in Arkansas, Florida, Missouri, Ohio, Oklahoma, and South Dakota.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Anthony Pro-Life America president Marjorie Dannenfelser stated her belief that other states may try to replicate Proposition 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Rene Almeling and Adora Svitak, respectively a sociology professor and graduate student at Yale University, wrote that a national abortion ban remained a possibility, even after California's passage of Proposition 1, if Republicans regain full control of the federal government in the 2024 elections.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] In response to the results of the abortion ballot measures, Kilgore wrote that "[t]he door to state abortion bans opened by the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Supreme Court earlier this year when it reversed *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] A 2019 study by the Kaiser Family Foundation determined that the county's residents had to travel at least 50 miles to access an abortion provider.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Bay Area News Group reporter Marisa Kendall stated that support for Proposition 1 was tied to Newsom's support in California, "Newsom backed Prop.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] A KFF and AP VoteCast poll conducted between October 31 and November 8 found that 44% of California voters and 55% of California women aged 18–49 said *Roe*'s overturning was a major factor in getting them to vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Compared to the other ballot measures, Proposition 1 was the most popular across the state, particularly along the Pacific coast, where Democrats generally outnumber Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Additionally, the ballot measure's performance in each county nearly matched Newsom's performance in the gubernatorial election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] In 2023, the California State Legislature introduced a series of abortion-related legislation designed to further entrench reproductive rights in the state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Atkins proposed two bills that would prevent insurers from inflicting penalties on California providers who perform abortions and allow physician assistants to perform first-trimester abortions without a physician supervising them.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Legislation introduced by Assemblymembers Tasha Boerner and Rebecca Bauer-Kahan would redefine eligibility from "pregnant women" to "pregnant people" to ensure abortion access for transgender men and non-binary people.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-california-proposition-1-p02] Assemblymember Mia Bonta put forward a bill prohibiting reverse keyword and geofence warrants for California law enforcement and disallowing California-based companies from complying with them, which could be used to identify people who searched for or sought out abortion services.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The **2022 Kansas abortion referendum** was a rejected legislatively referred constitutional amendment to the Kansas Constitution that appeared on the ballot on August 2, 2022, alongside primary elections for statewide offices, with early voting from July 13.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] If enacted, the amendment would have declared that the Kansas Constitution does not guarantee a right to abortion, giving the Kansas state government power to prosecute individuals involved in abortions, and further declared that the Kansas government is not required to fund abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] On June 24, 2022, six weeks before the referendum, the Supreme Court's ruling in *Dobbs v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Jackson Women's Health Organization* overturned *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Wade,* allowing individual states to ban abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] While the Kansas referendum had already been scheduled, the *Dobbs* decision greatly increased the impact of its results, both in terms of its potential effects and as a bellwether of voter sentiment about abortion bans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The amendment was ultimately defeated by an 18-point margin, which was partially attributed to higher-than-usual turnout and an increase in voter registration in the run-up to the referendum.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] In 2015, the state legislature passed the Kansas Unborn Child Protection from Dismemberment Abortion Act, which would prohibit dilation and evacuation abortions, which accounted for 9% of abortions in Kansas, with few exceptions, such as to preserve the life of the mother.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] In response, two abortion providers in Overland Park and others sued the state in the Shawnee County District Court, arguing that sections 1 and 2 of the constitution's Bill of Rights recognized a "fundamental right to abortion".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The court agreed, blocking the law from taking into effect.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] As such, the state attorney general appealed the case, titled *Hodes & Nauser v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Derek Schmidt*, to the Kansas Court of Appeals.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] It issued a 7–7 decision in January 2016, effectively upholding the district court's decision.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The state then appealed again to the state supreme court, with oral arguments heard in March 2017.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] It argued that the state constitution couldn't protect abortion rights since abortion was mostly illegal when it was drafted in 1859 and that physicians had other ways to perform second-trimester abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The court published its 6–1 ruling to affirm the lower courts' judgement on April 26, 2019, which stated that the first section of the state bill of rights in which "all men are possessed of equal and inalienable natural rights" include "a woman's right to make decisions about her body".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The decision also stated that the right to abortion may only be infringed if "the State has a compelling interest, and has narrowly tailored its actions to that interest".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The proposed amendment was first introduced in the Legislature as House Concurrent Resolution 5019 and Senate Concurrent Resolution 1613 in mid-January 2020, nearly nine months after the ruling, which would be overruled by the amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Its title of "Value Them Both" refers to the amendment's opening line which laid out the supposed rationale behind it, i. e., to "value both women and children".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] It was modeled after a similar amendment to the Constitution of Tennessee which was also a reaction to a similar ruling by their Supreme Court.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] After vigorous protests from groups supporting and opposing the proposal, it failed in a vote in the Kansas House of Representatives, due to four Republicans voting against it.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] State representative Don Hineman, who voted against, said that the statewide vote should be held in November, and that his vote was not in contradiction to his "staunch pro-life record".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Almost exactly a year after its first introduction, the proposal was re-introduced as House Concurrent Resolution 5003.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Several amendments were introduced to change the dates of which the referendum would be held.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Jackson Women's Health Organization* case might also energize pro-choice voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Ultimately, none of these amendments were successful and in late January 2021, the resolution passed both houses on party-line votes, surpassing the two-thirds threshold needed for a constitutional amendment to be put before the voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The language of the bill — in which a "yes" vote would remove constitutional protections for abortion in all instances — was described as being intentionally misleading, due to the unpopularity of blanket restrictions on abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] It was put on the ballot through a house resolution passed in early 2021 with the goal of superseding a decision by the Kansas Supreme Court in 2019 that the state constitution protected a woman's access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Being the first abortion-related constitutional amendment on the ballot since the Supreme Court of the United States overturned the landmark *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, it was considered a bellwether over Americans' view on abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The Kansas referendum was also viewed as significant because neighboring states (such as Missouri and Oklahoma) are Republican-leaning and are more restrictive on abortion access.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The referendum was the first of five abortion-related ballot measures in the U.S. in 2022: the others were held on Election Day for the general election (November 8) in California, Kentucky, Michigan, Montana, and Vermont.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Because of this, the referendum was covered by media outlets worldwide.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Supporters called their proposal the **Value Them Both Amendment**, and it was referred to as such in the "explanatory statement" as such on the ballot (on which the referendum appeared under the title "Question Submitted: Constitutional Amendment").
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The referendum was also referred to as **Amendment 2**.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The leading organization in favor of the measure's passage was the Value Them Both Association, an umbrella group of anti-abortion organizations.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The Catholic dioceses in Kansas and many evangelical Christian groups also supported the measure.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The leading group against the measure was *Kansans for Constitutional Freedom*.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Its passage would also be detrimental to the future of abortion in Kansas as Republicans could use its two-thirds supermajority to override a veto by Laura Kelly, the Democratic governor of Kansas, of an abortion ban or restriction that would be illegal under the 2019 state supreme court case.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Saying that she opposed legislation that "interfered with a [woman's freedom]" to make "reproductive healthcare decisions [with] her physician", Kelly had faced a challenge in the concurrent gubernatorial election by Derek Schmidt, the Republican Attorney General who praised the overturn of *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Wade* and defended the state in the state court case.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Had the ballot measure passed, and had Schmidt won the election, Republicans would theoretically only need a simple majority to pass such legislation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The bill additionally stated that the government of Kansas is not required to fund abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] In an effort to appeal to the broader electorate, both sides of the debate tried to paint their preferred choice as more moderate than the opposite side.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Supporters of the "yes" vote said that the amendment would give voters the ability "to weigh in directly on the ballot so that we can pass [abortion] laws".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] They have also claimed that the amendment would allow for "common sense abortion limits", and said that the *Hodes & Nauser v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Schmidt* case, which protected the right to abortion, needed to be overruled, since it could be used to nullify existing abortion restrictions in Kansas, such as a ban on most abortions after 22 weeks and a requirement for parental consent.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Meanwhile, supporters of the "no" vote", i.e. opponents of the amendment, and legal experts said that, while the language of the amendment did not specifically reference an abortion ban, state legislators would be empowered to pass such legislation, and would likely do so.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] State representative Lindsay Vaughn also added that the right to abortion is a non-negotiable human right that should not be up for a popular vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Many commentators, on both sides of the issue, brought up the history of Kansas as a free state with respect to the issue of slavery in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Opponents and proponents of the measure collectively spent $22 million on the referendum campaign.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Abortion rights groups spent $11.3 million, while abortion opponents spent almost $11.1 million.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Of the funding in support of the proposed amendment, more than $4.3 million was contributed by Roman Catholic dioceses and the Kansas Catholic Conference.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Kansans for Life reported spending $2.7 million (split between its own efforts and its contribution to the main "vote yes" organization), and Susan B.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Anthony Pro-Life America reported spending $1.4 million.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Of the funding opposing the proposed amendment, Planned Parenthood affiliates and other abortion-rights organizations contributed nearly $2.3 million; approximately $1.5 million was contributed by Sixteen Thirty Fund, and $1.25 million was contributed by Michael Bloomberg.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] "No" won all four congressional districts, including three that were represented by Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Meanwhile, on the same day as the referendum, President Joe Biden released a statement praising the measure's defeat, while criticizing the US Supreme Court for overturning *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] In response to the referendum results, several national Democratic Party leaders, including Senators Elizabeth Warren and Brian Schatz, argued that the party's candidates should emphasize reproductive rights in the 2022 midterm elections.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Analysts noted that the "No" option outperformed Biden's vote share in the 2020 presidential election in every county, and won in several suburban counties where Trump had won a majority in 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] There had been initial fears that holding a referendum alongside statewide primaries (rather than the general election) would suppress turnout, but this ultimately did not happen.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] *The Topeka Capital-Journal* reported that Democratic primaries were less contentious, and many Democratic candidates ran unopposed, meaning that Democrats would otherwise be unlikely to vote in the primaries.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The turnout of nearly 50% exceeded a 36% turnout predicted by Secretary of State Scott Schwab a few days before the referendum, extrapolating from factors such as past turnout data.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] He also acknowledged that the ballot measure "has increased voter interest in the election".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The turnout rate was nearly double that in the 2018 primary election, and nearly two-thirds of that in the 2020 general election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] Voter turnout set a Kansas record for primary elections, with the referendum increasing political mobilization.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] The term "Free-stater" has particular resonance in Kansas due to the history of conflict over slavery there.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kansas-abortion-referendum] A 2024 study in *American Politics Research* found that the referendum, which took place alongside a primary election, "mobilized an electorate that had more women and young people, fewer Republicans, and more first-time voters than a normal primary".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Kentucky was one of six states to vote on an abortion-related referendum as part of the 2022 elections, alongside California, Michigan, Montana, Kansas, and Vermont.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] This was in the immediate aftermath of the United States Supreme Court's decision in *Dobbs v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, which held that the United States Constitution did not confer a right to an abortion, allowing individual states to permit, regulate, or prohibit abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] In 2022, Kentucky was the only one of these states with both an active abortion ban and an active abortion referendum.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Following the results of the referendum, Kentucky's abortion ban was contested by abortion providers to the Kentucky Supreme Court, which in February 2023 ruled that the providers lacked standing to challenge the state's abortion ban.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] As of 2024, abortions remain illegal in Kentucky.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Supreme Court's decision in *Dobbs*, a trigger law went into effect banning any abortions in Kentucky unless necessary to prevent death or physical impairment of a pregnant woman.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] This ban was temporarily blocked by a court on June 30, 2022, then re-instated by a higher court on August 1, 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] The amendment was introduced in the Kentucky Legislature in March 2021 as HB 91.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] It was supported by Kentucky Right to Life and opposed by the ACLU of Kentucky.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Supporters of the amendment organized as the group **Yes for Life**, while opponents of the amendment organized as the group **Protect Kentucky Access**.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Amendments to the Kentucky Constitution require 3/5 support in both houses of the General Assembly and a majority vote by referendum; they can not be vetoed by the governor.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] The amendment was first introduced on January 5 in the 2021 General Assembly as House Bill 91 by representative Joseph Fischer.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] The bill subsequently passed both houses.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] The bill was initially passed by the house on February 25 by a 76–20 vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Representatives Tom Burch and Reginald Meeks, who did not vote, later modified their votes to nay.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] The bill was approved by the senate on March 30 by a 32–6 vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Supporters of the "Yes" campaign claimed that the amendment was a safeguard against judicial activism and a potential state-level *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Wade* decision by the Kentucky Supreme Court.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] They argued that late-term abortion and public funding for abortion would become common in Kentucky were the amendment to fail.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Supporters of the "No" campaign claimed that abortion would become permanently banned in Kentucky were the amendment to succeed, and that exceptions for rape and incest could never become law under the proposed amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] "No" won three of six congressional districts, including two that elected Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] The uniform results in Kentucky, Montana, California, Vermont, and Michigan abortion referendums were seen as a victory for the pro-choice movement, and were praised by pro-choice organizations and activists.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Anti-abortion organizations such as Susan B.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] Anthony Pro-Life America attributed their losses to misinformation and large amounts of outside spending from the pro-choice side.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] State attorney general Daniel Cameron stated that the failure of the amendment should have no impact on whether the Kentucky Constitution contains the right to an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-kentucky-amendment-2] On February 16, 2023, the Kentucky Supreme Court ruled that abortion providers lacked standing to challenge the state's abortion ban, but did not elaborate on whether or not the Kentucky Constitution secured abortion rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Jackson Women's Health Organization* ruling which overturned *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Wade*, access to abortion in Michigan became regulated by a 1931 law which criminalized abortion except in cases where the mother's life was at risk.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The law was ruled unconstitutional by Michigan Court of Claims Judge Elizabeth L.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Gleicher, characterizing the law as a violation of due process; however, the case was appealed to the Michigan Supreme Court.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Regardless of the outcome of that appeal, there was no clear constitutional protection for abortion access in Michigan, making further potential regulation of abortion access by the legislature possible.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The amendment was introduced to overturn the 1931 abortion ban and make the right to "reproductive freedom" explicit in the Michigan Constitution.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The Reproductive Freedom For All ballot committee gathered 753,759 signatures for the constitutional amendment, the most ever gathered for a ballot measure in state history, and more than enough for it to be placed on the 2022 ballot.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] On August 31, the Board of State Canvassers, responsible for determining whether candidates and initiatives should be placed on the ballot, deadlocked 2–2, with challengers arguing that the initiative's wording was poorly spaced.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] On September 9, the Michigan Supreme Court ruled 5-2 that the initiative should be placed on the November ballot.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Restrictions on reproductive rights must be implemented in the "least restrictive means", and with a "compelling" interest.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] An individual’s right to reproductive freedom shall not be denied, burdened, nor infringed upon unless justified by a compelling state interest achieved by the least restrictive means.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] (2) The state shall not discriminate in the protection or enforcement of this fundamental right.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] (3) The state shall not penalize, prosecute, or otherwise take adverse action against an individual based on their actual, potential, perceived, or alleged pregnancy outcomes, including but not limited to miscarriage, stillbirth, or abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Nor shall the state penalize, prosecute, or otherwise take adverse action against someone for aiding or assisting a pregnant individual in exercising their right to reproductive freedom with their voluntary consent.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] (5) This section shall be self-executing.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Any provision of this section held invalid shall be severable from the remaining portions of this section.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The proposal's main opponents, Citizens to Support MI Women and Children, have called Proposal 3 "extreme", arguing that it could invalidate 41 state laws related to abortion and other issues (including prostitution, statutory rape, and human cloning).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] They have argued that due to the right to reproductive freedom applying to "all individuals", that it would repeal the requirement for minors to receive parental consent in order to receive an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The group also asserted that the proposal would allow any "attending health care professional" to perform an abortion (a definition under state law that includes athletic trainers and masseuses), and repeal safety standards and inspections of abortion clinics.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] University of Detroit Mercy associate law professor Michelle Richards argued that such issues could still be regulated under Proposal 3, as a compelling interest to protect the safety and welfare of residents.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Opponents of Proposal 3 claimed that the amendment would codify an "unlimited right to abortion" by allowing abortions up to the last week of pregnancy for any reason.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] It was also argued by opponents that Proposal 3 would allow minors to receive puberty blockers, castration, or a hysterectomy without parental consent, under an interpretation of the proposal that classified these procedures as falling under "infertility" and "sterilization".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The Michigan Supreme Court will have to rule on the precise effects of the amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Reproductive Freedom for All has received $44 million, mostly from groups such as the ACLU, Planned Parenthood, and NARAL and Sam Bankman-Fried.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Meanwhile, the Citizens to Support MI Women and Children has raised almost $17 million from groups such as the Michigan Catholic Conference and Right to Life of Michigan.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Both committees have spent millions of dollars on advertising, including on TV and digital ads.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Opinion polls for the first few months before the referendum indicated significant majority support for the amendment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Its popularity waned from the initial summer backlash from the *Dobbs* decision, but nonetheless, the amendment had a clear lead in the polls throughout the campaign.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Proposal 3 was approved with 56.66% of the vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Among the factors contributing to the proposal's passage were the increased participation in the midterm election by younger voters, and a heightened involvement exhibited by non-activist Michiganders.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] Results by congressional district are shown below.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] "Yes" won nine of 13 congressional districts, including two that elected Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] In the wake of the constitutional amendment's approval, the 1931 abortion law was repealed on April 5, 2023.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The Reproductive Health Act, which repealed several abortion restrictions, was enacted on November 21, 2023.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The act also repealed a Republican-passed 10-year-old law requiring a separate health insurance add-on for abortion coverage that critics called "rape insurance".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The America Project, a Donald Trump-aligned organization, funded a partial recount of this proposal, as well as 2022 Michigan Proposal 2, despite their passage by wide margins.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The recount was spearheaded by Jerome Jay Allen of the conservative group Election Integrity Fund and Force.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] The recount lasted two weeks, and added 116 "yes" votes and 7 "no" votes to the totals.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] This led to calls to tighten recount rules, to disallow, or make more expensive for those who request them, frivolous recounts with no chance of changing the vote outcome.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-michigan-proposal-3] On July 9, 2024, governor Gretchen Whitmer signed a bill that would restrict recounts to cases where there was a reasonable chance the election outcome could be flipped.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] A general election was held in Montana on November 8, 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Both of Montana's seats in the United States House of Representatives, all of the seats in the Montana House of Representatives, and half of the seats in the Montana Senate were up for election, as well as various local offices and ballot measures.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] The primary election was held on June 7, 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Republicans won both of Montana's seats in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Randy Pinocci ran unopposed for District 1.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] In District 5 Republican Ann Bukacek defeated Democrat John Repke.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] 25 of the 50 seats in the Montana Senate were up for election in 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] All 100 seats in the Montana House of Representatives were up for election in 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Incumbent Jim Rice defeated Bill D'Alton.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Rice is the longest serving member of the Montana Supreme Court having been appointed in 2001 by Judy Martz.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Incumbent Ingrid Gustafson defeated James Brown.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] While the candidates are non-partisan, this race became overtly partisan.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Brown received significant Republican support, including endorsement by Governor Gianforte, prior to the primaries.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Both candidates received significant campaign contributions from outside groups.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-montana-elections] Montana Free Press reported $3 million spent by outside groups, making it the most money ever spent in a Montana Supreme Court race.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Elections were held in the United States on November 8, 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In these midterm elections, which occurred during incumbent Democratic president Joe Biden's term, all 435 seats in the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] House of Representatives and 35 of the 100 seats in the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Senate were contested to determine the 118th United States Congress.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Thirty-nine state and territorial U.S. gubernatorial elections, as well as numerous state and local elections, were also contested.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This was the first election affected by the 2022 redistricting that followed the 2020 census.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Republican Party ended unified Democratic control of Congress and the presidency by winning a majority in the House of Representatives while Democrats expanded their Senate majority.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Midterm elections typically see the incumbent president's party lose a substantial number of seats, but Democrats outperformed the historical trend and a widely anticipated red wave did not materialize.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans narrowly won the House due to their overperformance in the nation's four largest states: Texas, Florida, New York and California.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats increased their seats in the Senate by one, as they won races in critical battleground states, where voters rejected Donald Trump-aligned Republican candidates.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This was the fifth election cycle in history in which the president's party gained Senate seats and simultaneously lost House seats in a midterm, along with 1914, 1962, 1970, and 2018.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Democratic Party's strength in state-level and senatorial elections was unexpected, as well as historic.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] They won a net gain of two seats in the gubernatorial elections, flipping the governorships in Arizona, Maryland, and Massachusetts; conversely, Republicans flipped Nevada's governorship.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In the state legislative elections, Democrats flipped both chambers of the Michigan Legislature, the Minnesota Senate, and the Pennsylvania House, and achieved a coalition government in the Alaska Senate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] As a result of these legislative and gubernatorial results, Democrats gained government trifectas in Michigan for the first time since 1985, and in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Minnesota for the first time since 2015.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] 2022 is the first midterm since 1934 in which the president's party did not lose any state legislative chambers or incumbent senators.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] It was also the first midterm since 1986 in which either party achieved a net gain of governorships while holding the presidency, and the first since 1934 in which the Democrats did so under a Democratic president.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Governor Ron DeSantis of Florida, previously considered one of the nation's most contested swing states, won reelection in a landslide, as did Senator Marco Rubio.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] More generally, Florida was one of the only states where some evidence of the predicted 'red wave' materialized.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Voters in Nevada also approved ranked voting over first-past-the-post, while those in Illinois and Tennessee approved a state constitutional right to collectively bargain and a right-to-work law, respectively.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Issues that favored Democrats included significant concern over perceived extremism and threats to democracy among many Trump-endorsed Republican candidates, the unpopularity of the Supreme Court's *Dobbs* decision on abortion that reversed *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Wade*, the weariness of a potential Trump 2024 campaign, and backlash over the January 6 United States Capitol attack.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Candidate quality played a major role, particularly in the Senate, as many Republican candidates became embroiled in scandals during the campaign that led to underperformances in key races.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] On the other hand, Democrats' political prospects were weighed down by the 2021–2022 inflation spike, which Republicans blamed on President Biden and the Democratic-controlled Congress.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] General turnout and turnout among voters aged 18–29, who are a strongly Democratic constituency, were the second-highest (after 2018) of any midterm since the 1970 U.S. elections.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The elections maintained demographic trends that began in 2012, in which Republicans made gains among the working class, especially White people.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans continued their trend since 2016 of making gains among minorities, including Latinos.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats continued their trend of improved performance among White college-educated voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] After the 2020 elections, Democrats had a federal trifecta for the first time since the 111th United States Congress in 2011.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This gave them a relatively straightforward path to enacting legislation, but the presence of more centrist or conservative Democrats, namely Joe Manchin and Kyrsten Sinema, meant that most of the more expansive and often more progressive legislation was blocked.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In addition, the incumbent president almost always loses seats in Congress and often at least one chamber or overall control, in particular since the post-war period.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Going into 2022, Republicans capitalized on high inflation, crime, and gas prices, and gained a substantial lead in the election climate towards 2022 results similar to the red wave of 2010.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Wade* by the Supreme Court of the United States in the June 2022 *Dobbs v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] After suffering losses in 2021, progressives within the Democratic Party saw improved but mixed results in 2022, with both progressives and moderates winning important races.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In 2022, Democratic campaign arms aided radical-right candidates in Republican primary elections, believing they would be easier opponents in the general election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Republican primary candidates who had been endorsed by Trump tended to win, with his support being crucial for many, though his percentage was lower than in previous years, largely due to him taking riskier endorsements.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Generally, candidates that received Trump's endorsements were on the far right and those who supported his false claims that there was widespread fraud in the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Trump issued primary endorsements to 37 candidates who ran in the general elections in November that were rated as competitive by *The Cook Political Report with Amy Walter*.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The economy, inflation in particular, remained the top issue for voters throughout 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] According to an October 2022 Monmouth University poll, 82 percent of Americans considered inflation to be an "extremely or very essential issue" for the government to handle, and seven in ten Americans disapproved of Biden's handling of the cost of living rise.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* that overturned *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats tried to pass a federal law to protect the right to abortion but did not have enough support in the Senate, and abortion was prioritized as an issue for the general elections.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Some Democrats, including party strategists and pollsters, were divided on whether this could help them or if focusing on the economy and inflation, as the latter seemed to grow a bigger concern among voters in the fall, was a better strategy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This led some observers, as well as several major news outlets, including among others ABC News, CNN, and NBC News, to question whether their focus on abortion was the best strategy to avoid losses in the midterms and if it had lost significance since spring.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The *Dobbs* ruling made abortion more important for voters, with a rise in support among voters, particularly young women, for Democrats coming after the decision; at least six states had an abortion-related ballot initiative, the most ever in a single year.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] After *Dobbs*, Republicans attempted to pass several anti-abortion laws at the state level where they were not fully banned, including removal of incest and rape exceptions, but suffered from internal division on the issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Lindsey Graham, who was not up for reelection in 2022, introduced a federal bill to ban abortions after 15 weeks; most Republicans argued that abortion regulations should be left to the states, and Graham's proposal received a mixed response among Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In several states, such as Indiana, South Carolina, and West Virginia, they struggled to pass new state-level bans and restrictions on abortion despite controlling the state legislatures because they could not agree on their restrictions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Mass shootings made gun violence and crime more important issues for voters, in particular after the Robb Elementary School shooting in May 2022, which is common in the aftermath of school shootings.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Bipartisan Safer Communities Act, which passed in June 2022, provided extended gun-safety laws and was touted by Biden and Democrats.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Despite this, Republicans maintained a lead among voters who cited crime as a major issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans blamed the increase in violent crime and homicides in 2020 and 2021 on progressives and liberals, as well as attempts to "defund the police", a slogan supported by racial justice protesters but eventually rejected by Biden.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In a June 2022 Supreme Court decision, the Roberts Court further expanded the right to keep and bear arms in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats pushed for stricter gun laws, including a ban on assault weapons, while Republicans sought to protect legal access to guns and the Second Amendment to the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats also argued that Republicans regaining power would harm U.S. governance, citing the many Republican Trump-endorsed candidates who denied the results of the 2020 U.S. presidential election, which news outlets tracked.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] As of July 2022, at least 120 Republican candidates endorsed by Trump were 2020 election deniers, a majority of whom ran for the House.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Democratic Party filed lawsuits to remove Green Party candidates from the ballot, most notably the North Carolina Green Party candidate Matthew Hoh in the 2022 United States Senate election in North Carolina, citing an ongoing investigation into the party for fraudulant signatures.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Their warning that Greens could divide progressive voters and give Republicans wins in tight races nonetheless received widespread criticism, and Hoh appeared on the ballot.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans argued for parents having more control over what their children are taught in schools, being concerned in particular by discussions on topics such as race, gender identity, and sexuality.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats dismissed these concerns as a push for censorship, saying that it would especially harm LGBT students.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This came amid increased efforts among Republicans to ban books that discuss those topics, particularly in Republican-controlled states like Florida.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Twenty Republican candidates promulgated the litter boxes in schools hoax, which emerged largely as backlash against recognition of gender variance in schools.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] House minority leader Kevin McCarthy vowed to "recover lost learning from school closures" during the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In this election, climate change was a significant issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] 71% of voters considered climate change as a serious problem, even though there were differences in the level of concern.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] One poll showed that for 51% of voters climate change was one of the more important issues.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] According to another poll, 64% of people of color were more likely to vote for a candidate that is addressing climate change as one of the three most important points in their agenda.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] A third poll showed that 9% of voters considered climate change as the most important issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Progressive Democrats pushed for legislation to combat the negative effects of climate change, including incentives towards the adoption of renewable energy and electric cars.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In August 2022, Biden signed into law the Inflation Reduction Act, which also included climate change-related policies to address it, and has been described as the first major or significant climate change law, as well as the largest investment to fight climate change in U.S. history.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Immigration is among the issues where the United States is divided the most.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Biden revoked some of Trump's anti-immigration policies but not others, and Republicans pledged to continue Trump's hardline policies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] An increase of over 385% in border encounters from 2020 to 2022 gave Republicans an edge over Democrats, as Republicans blamed it on Biden and Democrats, and polling showed that voters moderately preferred Republicans over Democrats for solving immigration problems.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In a September 2022 political stunt, Florida governor Ron DeSantis had migrants sent to Martha's Vineyard.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This was also done by Republican governors in Arizona and Texas who sent migrants to northerner, more liberal states, which was criticized by Biden, Democrats, and migrant rights groups as a "cruel political theatre".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] A majority of voters were found to support student loan forgiveness in the run-up to the election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In November 2022, a federal judge in Texas struck down Biden's student loan plan.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In response, Biden extended a moratorium on the plan from January 2023 to June 2023.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans were benefiting from Biden's low U.S. presidential approval ratings, hovering from 30–40% for much of the year.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] His ratings briefly increased after several legislative victories in August and September 2022; by October, they again plateaued when voters focused back on the state of the economy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Biden avoided intervention in several key Senate races, among them Arizona, Georgia, and New Hampshire, where his ratings were further below his presidential approval nationally.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Russian invasion of Ukraine was the major foreign policy issue, shifting support for Biden and highlighting the Republican Party's perceived support for Russia and Vladimir Putin.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] With a total of almost 17 billion U.S. dollars in expenditure, the election campaigns for the 2022 midterm elections were the most expensive in the history of the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Thirty-five of the 100 seats in the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Senate were up for election, including all 34 Class 3 senator seats.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Concurrent with the regularly scheduled Class 3 elections, a special election was held to fill a Class 2 vacancy in Oklahoma.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] As senators serve six-year terms, the last regularly scheduled elections for Class 3 senators were held in 2016.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The winners of the Senate elections were sworn in on January 3, 2023, for the 118th U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Going into the election, Democrats and Republicans both held 50 seats, but Democrats had a majority due to their control of the vice presidency, which has the power to break ties in the Senate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In the Senate elections, Republicans defended 21 seats, including six seats left open by retirements.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats defended fourteen seats, one of which was an open seat.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This was the third consecutive midterm election in the incumbent president's first term in which the party not occupying the White House was able to win control of the House but was unable to win the Senate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats performed better than expected in New Hampshire, Pennsylvania (where they gained a seat – the sole flipping seat), and Nevada, which allowed them to retain control of the Senate, and with an increased majority after winning the runoff election in Georgia.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Two special elections took place in 2022 to replace senators who resigned during the 117th U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In early December 2022, Kyrsten Sinema of Arizona announced she would leave the Democratic Party and register as an independent.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] House of Representatives were up for election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Forty-nine representatives and one non-voting delegate (30 Democrats, 20 Republicans) did not seek re-election, and three seats were vacant at the time of the election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The incumbents in the 2022 elections were determined in the 2020 U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] House of Representatives elections and subsequent special elections.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] These elections were the first conducted after the 2020 U.S. redistricting cycle, causing several districts to lack an incumbent or have multiple incumbents.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats held a 220–212 majority at the time of the election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The race was competitive and closer than expected, with Republicans gaining control of the chamber with a slim 222–213 majority.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Elections were held for the governorships of 36 U.S. states and three insular areas.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] As most governors serve four-year terms, the last regularly scheduled elections for most seats up for election in 2022 were held in 2018.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The governors of New Hampshire and Vermont each serve two-year terms, so incumbents in these two states were determined in 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Prior to the election, Republicans held a total of 28 seats, 20 of which were up for election in 2022, and Democrats held 22 seats, 16 of which were up for election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats picked up the seats of retiring and term-limited Republican incumbents in Arizona, Maryland, and Massachusetts, while Republicans held onto Arkansas.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democratic incumbents won high-profile contests in Michigan and Wisconsin, while Democrat Josh Shapiro's defeat of Republican Doug Mastriano allowed Democrats to retain control of Pennsylvania's gubernatorial office.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] A Democratic incumbent also prevailed in a closely contested race in Kansas, while the party held onto Oregon in another closely contested race.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Tina Kotek of Oregon is set to be one of the first lesbian governors in the United States, along with Maura Healey in Massachusetts.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats made a further gain in Arizona, which set the record for most female governors in U.S. history.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The sole gain for Republicans was in Nevada, where Joe Lombardo narrowly defeated the incumbent Democratic governor Steve Sisolak.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Various state-wide executive positions across several states held elections in 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] State attorneys general were elected in thirty U.S. states, three territories, and one federal district.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The previous elections for this group of states took place in 2018.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The attorney general of Vermont serves two-year terms and was last elected in 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] While Democrats flipped Vermont and Charity Clark became the state's first female attorney general, one notable Republican upset was Brenna Bird's narrow win over Tom Miller, the incumbent Democratic attorney general of Iowa and the longest-serving state attorney general in U.S. history.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Secretaries of state were elected in twenty-seven U.S. states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The secretary of state of Vermont serves two-year terms and was last elected in 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] State treasurers and equivalents were elected in twenty-seven U.S. states, plus a special election in Utah.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The treasurer of Vermont serves two-year terms and was last elected in 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Numerous states held judicial elections in 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans gained a majority on the North Carolina Supreme Court by picking up two seats, raising the possibility of mid-decade redistricting.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In another election with major redistricting implications, Republicans retained a majority on the Supreme Court of Ohio.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In 2022, 46 states held regularly scheduled elections in 88 legislative chambers, although not all seats were up in the legislatures holding elections, as some states use staggered terms.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Louisiana, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Virginia did not hold regularly scheduled state legislative elections, as those states all hold such elections in odd-numbered years.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The District of Columbia and the U.S. territories of American Samoa, Guam, and the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Virgin Islands also held legislative elections in 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] House of Representatives, these elections were the first conducted after the 2020 U.S. census and the 2022 U.S. redistricting.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Prior to the election, Republicans controlled 60 legislative chambers, Democrats controlled 37 chambers, and a cross-party coalition controlled the Alaska House of Representatives.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats successfully defended every legislative chamber they had held prior to the election, the first time the president's party accomplished this feat in a midterm since the 1934 U.S. elections.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] However, Republicans established a cross-party coalition in the Alaska House of Representatives, shifting the majority from a predominantly Democratic caucus to a predominantly Republican caucus.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats picked up the Pennsylvania House of Representatives, the Minnesota Senate, both state legislative chambers in Michigan, and also established a cross-party coalition in the Alaska Senate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats had not controlled the Michigan Senate since 1984, one reason being that although Democrats won the popular vote several times (2012, 2018, and 2020), Republicans continued to win more seats due to a more favorable map.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This map was redrawn by an independent commission in 2021, which was established by a 2018 ballot initiative.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] As a result of victories in state legislative and gubernatorial elections, Democrats gained government trifectas in Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, and Minnesota.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In addition, Republicans lost a trifecta in Arizona, which they held since 2009, while Democrats lost a trifecta in Nevada.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Following the election, although Republicans held trifectas in more states, more people lived in Democratic-controlled states than in Republican-controlled states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Though Republican governor Phil Scott won reelection, Democrats gained a veto-proof supermajority in both chambers of the Vermont General Assembly.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans gained supermajorities in the Wisconsin Senate, the North Carolina Senate, the South Carolina House of Representatives, and both chambers of the Florida Legislature.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] At the same time, the Republican Party fell short of attaining a supermajority in the Wisconsin State Assembly and the North Carolina House of Representatives, meaning that Democratic governors in both states will retain the ability to veto legislation that is passed without Democratic support.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Of the many proposed for 2022, 132 ballot measures were certified in 37 states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] During the August primaries, 59% of Kansas voters rejected their state's Value Them Both Amendment, which would have removed the right to an abortion from the Kansas Constitution.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] California voters considered Proposition 1 during the general election, which was approved, and amended the Constitution of California to explicitly grant the right to an abortion and contraceptives.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] All other abortion-related ballot measures also passed.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In Arizona, voters approved a ballot measure that limited medical debt interest rates.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In South Dakota, voters approved to expand Medicaid coverage as part of the Affordable Care Act.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In five states, voters were asked to make the possession and use of marijuana legal for people 21 and older.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In Maryland and Missouri, the measures were approved, while voters in Arkansas, as well as in North and South Dakota, rejected legalization.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In Colorado, voters approved the decriminalization and regulation of certain psychedelic plants and fungi.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Also on the ballot in five states were measures to abolish slavery in prisons.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Alabama, Tennessee, Oregon, and Vermont abolished slavery in prisons; the measure did not pass in Louisiana.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Since the beginning of 2022, elections were held for the office of mayor, as well as several other municipal and county-level positions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Major U.S. cities saw incumbent mayors re-elected, including Fort Smith, Arkansas (George McGill); Little Rock, Arkansas (Frank Scott Jr.); Tallahassee, Florida (John E.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Bass succeeded two-term incumbent Eric Garcetti, and in doing so became the first woman and the second Black person (after Tom Bradley) to be elected mayor of Los Angeles.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In San Bernardino, California, city worker Helen Tran was elected to replace incumbent John Valdivia, who was defeated in the blanket primary.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In Shreveport, Louisiana, incumbent Adrian Perkins lost re-election in the Louisiana primary, and was succeeded by the winner of the runoff on December 10, former city councilor Tom Arceneaux, who became the first Republican elected to the position in 28 years.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In Norman, Oklahoma, Larry Heikkila defeated one-term incumbent mayor Breea Clark.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] In Milwaukee, Wisconsin, acting mayor Cavalier Johnson defeated Bob Donovan in a special election to complete the term of Tom Barrett, who resigned in December 2021 to become the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] He is the first African-American and first millennial to be elected mayor of Milwaukee.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Several notable Native American tribes held elections for tribal executive positions during 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Central Council of the Tlingit and Haida Tribes of Alaska reelected tribal president Chalyee Éesh Richard Peterson to a fifth term; Lynn "Nay" Valbuena was also elected to serve a fifth term as chair of the San Manuel Band of Mission Indians.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Terry Rambler won election to a fourth consecutive term as chair of the San Carlos Apache Tribe.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Osage Nation principal chief Geoffrey Standing Bear, tribal council chief Beverly Kiohawiton Cook of the St.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Regis Mohawk Tribe, Mark Fox of the Three Affiliated Tribes, Jamie Azure of the Turtle Mountain Band of Chippewa Indians, Seneca Nation President Rickey Armstrong Sr., and Wampanoag Tribe of Gay Head Chairperson Cheryl Andrews-Maltais, were all reelected to third terms.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Chairman Marshalle Pierite of the Tunica-Biloxi Tribe, the Peoria Tribe of Indians of Oklahoma chief Craig Harper, as well as Prairie Band Potawatomi Nation tribal chairman Joseph Rupnik, were all reelected to a second term.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Also reelected were Salt River Pima–Maricopa Indian Community president Martin Harvier and Quapaw Nation chairman Joseph Byrd.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Bill Sterud was reelected as chair of the Puyallup Tribe; he first joined the Puyallup Tribal Council in 1978.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Brad KillsCrow was elected to his first full term as chief of the Delaware Tribe of Indians.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Milanovich was elected chairman of the Agua Caliente Band of Cahuilla Indians, replacing the retiring Jeff Grubbe.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Clayton Dumont Jr. won an open seat to become chairman of the Klamath Tribes, Arden L.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Kucate was elected governor of the Pueblo of Zuni, Kimberly Jenkins was elected chair of the Kaw Nation, and the Sisseton Wahpeton Oyate in the Dakotas elected J.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Garret Renville as their new tribal chair.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Lawrence Spottedbird won a contentious race to become chairman of the Kiowa Indian Tribe of Oklahoma.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Several tribal leaders were defeated when seeking reelection.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Buu Nygren defeated Jonathan Nez to become president of the Navajo Nation; Nygren's running mate, Richelle Montoya, is the first woman elected as Navajo Nation vice president.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Lora Ann Chaisson defeated August "Cocoa" Creppel in the election for principal chief of the United Houma Nation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Kasey Velasquez defeated chairwoman Gwendena Lee-Gatwood to become the second woman elected to lead the White Mountain Apache Tribe.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] RoseMary LaClair defeated incumbent Nooksack Indian Tribe chairman Roswell Cline Sr.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Former Red Lake Band of Chippewa chairman Floyd "Buck" Jourdain defeated incumbent chairman Darrell Seki Sr.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Ryman LeBeau defeated incumbent Harold Fraizer to become chairman-at-large of the Cheyenne River Sioux.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Yukon-Kuskokwim Delta Regional Tribal Government, formed in 2021 to unite 56 Yup'ik, Cup'ik, and Athabascan tribal governments in the Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta region, held its first elections in November 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] James Akerelrea was elected tribal president.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Several native groups weighed referendums regarding how tribal membership is determined.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Minnesota Chippewa Tribe, in two advisory referendums, approved removing blood quantum provisions from the tribe's constitution and allowing individual bands or reservations to determine membership requirements.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Shareholders of Sealaska Corporation, an Alaska Native corporation, similarly voted to drop blood quantum requirements.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The Confederated Tribes of the Grand Ronde Community of Oregon approved a measure to limit tribal disenrollment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] This table shows the partisan results of president, congressional, gubernatorial, and state legislative races held in each state and territory in 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] Note that not all states and territories hold gubernatorial, state legislative, and Senate elections in 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The five U.S. territories and Washington, D.C., do not elect members of the Senate, and the territories do not take part in presidential elections; instead, they each elect one of the six non-voting members of the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p01] The unicameral Nebraska Legislature and the governorship and legislature of American Samoa are elected on a non-partisan basis, and political party affiliation is not listed.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] The race for Congress was much closer than expected; control of Congress remained uncertain for several days, and the House remained too close to call for over a week, which was not thought to be likely in a national environment favorable to the Republican Party.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Organizations that make election calls projected on November 12 that the Democratic Party retained control of the Senate, while later projecting on November 15–16 that Republicans gained control over the House with a slim majority.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] 2022 is the first midterm since the 1934 U.S. elections in which the president's party did not lose any state legislative chambers or incumbent senators.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] This also marked the first time since the 1962 U.S. elections that Democrats made a net gain in the Senate while losing House seats.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In addition, Democrats gained a Senate seat in Pennsylvania where John Fetterman defeated Mehmet Oz, winning the seat of retiring Republican senator Pat Toomey, while they held their seat in Georgia in a runoff election, after no candidate won a majority of the vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Many factors have been attributed to the lack of a red wave and better-than-expected performance for Democrats, including the quality of candidates, youth turnout, and some vote splitting in key races.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Incumbent president Joe Biden, a Democrat, and incumbent Florida governor Ron DeSantis of the Republican Party, as well as reproductive rights, have been widely considered as the biggest winners, while former president Donald Trump was considered to be the biggest loser by the election results.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Sean Patrick Maloney, the chair of the Democratic House coalition's fundraising arm, lost his reelection bid after ten years in Congress.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Democrats made gains at the gubernatiorial level.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Gretchen Whitmer, the incumbent Democrat, won the 2022 Michigan gubernatorial election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] On the Republican side, incumbent governors performed well.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Greg Abbott won the 2022 Texas gubernatorial election, while Brian Kemp won the 2022 Georgia gubernatorial election; in both cases, they defeated the Democratic opponents, Beto O'Rourke and Stacey Abrams, respectively, who had lost by narrower margins in 2018.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In the 2022 Florida gubernatorial election, DeSantis won in a landslide, challenging the state's battleground status; results showed that he performed better than other Republicans among Hispanics, who got mixed results.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Both parties elected female governors, resulting in the most female governors in U.S. history.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Incumbent Laura Kelly of the Democratic Party narrowly won the 2022 Kansas gubernatorial election, while Sarah Huckabee Sanders of the Republican Party won the 2022 Arkansas gubernatorial election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Democrats also won the 2022 Arizona gubernatorial election, an office that was previously held by a term-limited Republican, as Katie Hobbs won over Kari Lake.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In state legislative elections, Democrats gained full control of government in Minnesota and made gains in Pennsylvania, where a more neutral, independent redrawn map (like in Michigan) gave them a shot to regain control of the state legislature.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In one of the most historic results of the night, Democrats gained a trifecta in Michigan for the first time since 1983.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] For over a week, control of the state legislatures of Alaska, Arizona, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania was not determined.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In Alaska, where for six years Democrats had a cross-coalition majority in the House with independents and moderate Republicans, a similar majority was established in the Senate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In New Hampshire, where Democrats made gains, the race for the House was so close that a series of recounts and legal challenges have followed, leaving the state of the race uncertain.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In Pennsylvania, Republicans retained control of the Senate but the House was too close; by November 16, Democrats regained control of the House for the first time since 2010.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Referendums to preserve or expand abortion access won in all six states where they were on the ballot (California, Kansas, Kentucky, Michigan, Montana, and Vermont).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Those related to increasing the minimum wage (Nebraska, Nevada, and Washington, D.C.) and expanding Medicaid coverage (South Dakota) also passed, while those related to cannabis legalization, some of which for medical uses and some for recreational usage, achieved mixed results.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Nevada also approved state ranked-choice voting election reform.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Those related to the abolition of penal labor in the United States also generally passed at the state level (Alabama, Tennessee, Oregon, and Vermont), with the exception of Louisiana.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Biden described the results as a "strong night" for Democrats, and he urged for cooperation in Congress.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Senator Lindsey Graham commented: "It's certainly not a red wave, that's for darn sure.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] But it is clear that we will take back the House." On November 9, when the results for the House were still uncertain, the Republican House leader Kevin McCarthy launched his bid to succeed long-time House Democrats leader Nancy Pelosi as Speaker of the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In a letter asking for support among Republicans, he wrote: "I trust you know that earning the majority is only the beginning.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Now, we will be measured by what we do with our majority.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Now the real work begins." On November 17, after Republicans were projected to win back the House, Pelosi announced that she would not seek reelection as speaker.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] On November 30, Hakeem Jeffries was selected by acclamation as the Democratic nominee for the House speakership.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Earlier on November 15, McCarthy won an internal Republican caucus poll as their speaker nominee.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] As several members of the Republican caucus did not vote for him and have expressed opposition to his speakership, it cast doubt on how the U.S. speaker election on January 3 would unfold.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] McCarthy would ultimately be elected speaker, but on the 15th ballot, due to internal divisions within the House Republican Conference.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] This resulted in the first speaker election since 1923 in which the speaker was not elected on the first ballot.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization* overturned the long-held precedent since 1973 of *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Wade* that gave a constitutional right to abortion, and the role of Trump and his imminent announcement of a campaign for the 2024 U.S. presidential election.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Increasing concerns over climate change and the higher approval of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 compared to the previous climate policy also played a role in it, as did turnout.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Whether youth turnout in particular helped to explain the results was also debated.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Democrats performed better than expected in states like New Hampshire, North Carolina, Ohio, and Pennsylvania, where Fetterman improved on Biden's 2020 results from white voters without a college degree.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Democrats also performed well in Colorado and New England, while Republicans made gains in Florida and New York.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Redistricting and gerrymandering affected results.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Gerrymanders in Florida, Georgia, Texas, and Ohio, gave Republicans an advantage in the House, while Democrats won 24 of 30 seats, or 80 percent, in Illinois, Nevada, New Mexico, and Oregon, with 54% of the popular vote across these four states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In New York, where Democrats suffered major losses, a gerrymander had been rejected by the courts, while gerrymanders in Florida and Tennessee gave Republicans more seats by virtue of the redistricted map being much more Republican-leaning.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Defensive gerrymanders helped both parties hold competitive seats in various states; Republican gains in New York and Democratic gains in North Carolina and Ohio were made possible because state supreme courts overturned gerrymanders passed by their state legislatures.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Republican attempts to stop early voting, such as the Saturday after Thanksgiving, were blocked by a state court.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] There was also some concern that Georgia's new state law, which shortened the runoff campaign period, would have negative effects on turnout; research shows that this particularly affects turnout among voters of color.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] By November 12, Democrats had retained the Senate, as the Democratic incumbents in Arizona and Nevada (Mark Kelly and Catherine Cortez Masto, respectively) were projected to have retained their seat.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Senate elections in which no Senate incumbents lost reelection.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Some gubernatorial races, such as in Arizona and Nevada, were not projected for several days, as they were too close call.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Kari Lake, the Republican candidate in Arizona who denied Trump's loss in 2020, refused to concede.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Over two weeks later, results in many races were still unknown.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Several tossup or key races were won by Democrats, including upsets in Colorado's 8th, North Carolina's 13th, and Washington's 3rd congressional districts, and narrowly missed by 550 votes a further upset for the Colorado's 3rd congressional district seat held by Lauren Boebert.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] On November 10–12, Republicans were favored to regain control of the House with a narrow majority of 3 seats (221–214) according to NBC News, with 218 seats needed for a majority.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] On November 13, Republicans and Democrats were projected to win 210–200 seats in the House according to *Decision Desk HQ*, 211–203 according to the Associated Press, and 211–206 according to ABC News.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] By November 14, Republicans were projected to possibly have a narrow majority in the House by as little as a single seat.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] On November 15, the projected seats in favor of Republicans were 217–203 per *Decision Desk HQ*, 217–205 per the Associated Press, and 215–207 per ABC News.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Later on the same day, *Decision Desk HQ* projected a Republican majority of the House, which was followed on November 16 by NBC News, and by the Associated Press on November 17.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] While Republicans won the popular vote by about 3 percent, the larger-than-reflected popular vote margin compared to seats was in part due to the fact Democrats did not contest several seats, which may have cost them about 1–2 percent in the final popular vote margin.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Although Republicans would have still won the popular vote, it underscored how close the race for the House was both in terms of the popular vote between each party and the number of seats they won.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Harry Enten of CNN observed that Republicans won the House and Senate popular votes by about 3 and 0.1 points, respectively, while Democrats won the gubernatorial popular vote by less than 0.3; this made the overall 2022 elections a historically close election cycle.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Enten attributed the overall close results to political polarization, which resulted in a shrinking of the pool of swing voters in the country.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Starting in 2012, Democrats suffered losses among the American working class, particularly whites.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Since 2016, Republicans made gains among minorities who are working class or Hispanic and Latino Americans; at the same time, Democrats continued to improve among college-educated whites, which helped them win in 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In 2022, Republicans made further gains among working-class peoples of color, and also among Hispanic voters, though not to the extent they expected, as Democrats continued to win a majority of their vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] The education divide remained polarized.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Compared to 2018, which was a blue wave election and saw higher turnout among Democrats, Republicans made gains among women, older people, suburban voters, and whites without college degrees.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Most American voters supported abortion rights; in the House, Republicans also won about a quarter of voters who said they support legal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Many pundits in the media failed to predict the Democratic resilient performance; Simon Rosenberg was one exception.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Republican pollsters such as the Trafalgar Group had a notable polling miss, with errors well outside the margin of error in races such as the 2022 U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Since 2016 and 2020, the latter of which was at the height of the COVID-19 pandemic, polling companies attempted to understand the misses in recent years and how to get better.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] There were also fewer polls in general, and a larger share came from partisan sources.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] On election eve, an unweighted average of 17 polls indicated that Republicans were expected to defeat Democrats by 2.5% in the generic congressional vote.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Polls were relatively good, especially when compared to 2020, though not as good as what *FiveThirtyEight*, a polling aggregator website, defines as the Gold Standard (2006–2012).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Their own forecasting model, which gave Republicans 59 and 84 percent of winning the Senate (slight favored) and the House (favored), respectively, assumed the possibility that polls underestimated Republicans; its polls-only version saw the Senate as a tossup.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Many pollsters had their own worries, and many feared they would miss Republican overperformances as it happened in 2016 and 2020 in particular.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Some environmental organizations and media described the result as a green wave, saying candidates addressing climate change did better compared to those considered who did not.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Among Republicans who won, they did not campaign against climate measures in the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Biden specifically thanked young climate voters.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] This was also reflected at the state and local level, where voters approved several climate-related initiatives.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Democrats performed well in states that could be key to the 2024 U.S. elections, and their better-than-expected performance may have avoided a damaging primary for the incumbent president; their net gain in the Senate could also help them as they face a harder map in the 2024 U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Senate elections, with many more seats to defend than Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Despite losses, Trump called the results a "great evening", though those close to him reported him "livid" and "furious with everyone" for the losses, in particular the Senate open seat in Pennsylvania.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] On November 15, the beginning of the Trump 2024 presidential campaign was officially announced.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] On November 18, attorney general Merrick Garland announced that he appointed Jack Smith as a special counsel to run part of the Department of Justice's probe into the January 6 Capitol attack, which could affect his eligibility under the 14th Amendment to the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Constitution as argued by some legal experts, as well as the FBI investigation into Trump's handling of government documents.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Trump's 2024 campaign announcement received wide media coverage and a mixed response from both Democrats and Republicans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Some Democrats warily welcomed the campaign, viewing Trump as beatable, while other Democrats, along with many observers and some Republicans, opposed it, citing the negative effects it could have on U.S. democracy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Some Republicans, consisting mostly of Trump loyalists, welcomed the campaign, while others opposed it, viewing him as a weak candidate who had lost Republicans the past several election cycles including the 2022 midterms and engaged in conspiracy theories, and also cited his legal troubles.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Voter turnout was relatively high by midterm standards, with an estimated 46.6% of the voting-eligible population casting a ballot.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] After the blue wave of 2018, it was the second highest since the 1970 U.S. elections.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] According to the Edison Research National Election Pool, the youth vote for the House was 63–35 in favor of Democrats.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Pollster Antonio Arellano commented that young voters were the only age group in which more than 50 percent of voters supported Democrats.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Arkansas, Massachusetts, and New York elected female governors for the first time, and Arkansas and Massachusetts became the first states in which women concurrently served as governor and lieutenant governor.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Alabama elected its first female senator, California elected a Latino senator for the first time, and Maryland elected its first African-American governor.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Markwayne Mullin became the first Native American to represent Oklahoma in the Senate since Robert Latham Owen retired in 1925.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] In Florida, Maxwell Frost became the first member of Generation Z elected to the House.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Marcy Kaptur's reelection made her the longest-serving woman in Congress following the completion of her term.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] Becca Balint became the first female member of Congress from Vermont—the last of the 50 states to elect a woman to Congress—and Summer Lee became the first black woman from Pennsylvania elected to Congress.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] The 2022 election was the first time that LGBTQ candidates appeared on the general election ballot in all 50 states and Washington, D.C.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] With their respective victories, Tina Kotek of Oregon and Maura Healey of Massachusetts became the first openly lesbian state governors.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/2022-united-states-elections-p02] James Roesener, elected to the New Hampshire House of Representatives, became the first transgender man to win a state legislative seat.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, abortion is a divisive issue in politics and culture wars.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Prior to the mid-19th century, English common law formed the basis of abortion law in the colonies and the early Republic.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut was the first state to regulate abortion in 1821; it outlawed abortion after quickening, the moment in pregnancy when the pregnant woman starts to feel the fetus's movement in the uterus, and forbade the use of poisons to induce one post-quickening.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various laws on abortion until the Supreme Court of the United States decisions of *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton* decriminalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The *Roe* decision imposed a federally mandated uniform framework for state legislation on the subject.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also established a minimal period during which abortion is legal, with more or fewer restrictions throughout the pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] That basic framework, modified in *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* (1992), remained nominally in place, although the effective availability of abortion varied significantly from state to state, as many counties had no abortion providers.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2022, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, ending protection of abortion rights by the United States Constitution and allowing individual states to regulate any aspect of abortion not preempted by federal law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 1976, the Republican Party has generally sought to restrict abortion access based on the stage of pregnancy or to criminalize abortion, whereas the Democratic Party has generally defended access to abortion and has made contraception easier to obtain.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion-rights movement advocates for patient choice and bodily autonomy, while the anti-abortion movement advocate that the fetus has a right to live.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Historically framed as a debate between the pro-choice and pro-life labels, most Americans agree with some positions of each side.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Support for abortion gradually increased in the U.S. beginning in the early 1970s, and stabilized during the 2010s.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion rate has continuously declined from a peak in 1980 of 30 per 1,000 women of childbearing age (15–44) to 11.3 by 2018.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2018, 78% of abortions were performed at 9 weeks or less gestation, and 92% of abortions were performed at 13 weeks or less gestation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 2023, medication abortions accounted for 63% of all abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Almost 25% of women will have had an abortion by age 45, with 20% of 30 year olds having had one.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019, 60% of women who had abortions were already mothers, and 50% already had two or more children.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Increased access to birth control has been statistically linked to reductions in the abortion rate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to decriminalize abortion prior to *Roe* was Hawaii.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2025, Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Illinois, Kansas, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New York, Ohio, Vermont, and Wyoming have a right to abortion in their state constitutions, either explicitly or as interpreted by the state supreme court.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Other states, such as Massachusetts and Oregon, protect abortion under state law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The state constitutions of Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana, Tennessee, and West Virginia explicitly contain no right to an abortion, while the state constitution of Nebraska prohibits abortion after the first trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In medical parlance, "abortion" refers only to the end of an intrauterine pregnancy before the embryo or fetus can survive outside the uterus.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This is inclusive of spontaneous abortion (more commonly referred to as miscarriage or early pregnancy loss) and to induced abortion, where a pregnancy is ended through medication or a medical procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion debate most commonly relates to the induced abortion of a pregnancy, which is also how the term "abortion" is used in a legal sense.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Because abortion has been politicized, there has been a proliferation of ill-defined, inconsistently applied terms with no medical or clinical basis.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Concepts like "late-term abortion", or "partial-birth abortion" are not medical terms and do not have clinical significance.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similarly, terms like "elective abortion" append unnecessary qualifiers that are not rooted in medical or legal distinctions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends using the terms "induced abortion" or simply "abortion" instead.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, some drugs that do not induce medical abortions, such as levonorgestrel, have been referred to as abortifacients by a US Senator.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion in what eventually became the United States was governed by English Common law, which held that abortion after quickening was murder.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was repeated by Henry de Bracton, Matthew Hale, and William Blackstone.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The common law on abortions before quickening was varying.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians argue that abortion was a fairly common practice in the history of the United States, and was not always controversial.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] At a time when society was more concerned with the more serious consequence of women becoming pregnant out of wedlock, family affairs were handled out of public view.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion did not become a public controversy until the health risk of unsafe abortions by (female) unlicensed practitioners was brought to the public attention in the 19th century.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] James Mohr wrote that even though pre-quickening abortion was legal in the first three decades of the 19th century, only 1 in 25 to 1 in 30 pregnancies ended in abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1850s and 1860s, this number had increased to 1 in 5 or 1 in 6.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Keown highlighted some challenges in pinning down the common law view, observing that "evidence of quickening would clearly facilitate prosecution".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the mid-18th century, Benjamin Franklin included a recipe for an abortifacient in a math textbook.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1728, Franklin condemned publisher Samuel Keimer for publishing an article on abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to biographer Walter Isaacson, Franklin did not have a strong view on the issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Speech of Polly Baker*, Franklin places the blame for abortion and infanticide on the sexual double standard against women.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1716, New York passed an ordinance prohibiting midwives from providing abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Founding Father and Second President of the United States John Adams praised the Spartan lawgiver Lycurgus for refusing his sister-in-law from having an abortion even though it prevented him from assuming power.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Thomas Jefferson wrote approving of a quote by Montesquieu that "‘there is among savages another custom . . . it is the cruel practice of abortion." Jefferson added that the Natives stopped the practice after becoming "civilized".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Within the context of a sex scandal, Connecticut became the first state to regulate abortion by statute in 1821.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1829, New York made post-quickening abortions a felony and pre-quickening abortions a misdemeanor.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was followed by 10 of the 26 states creating similar restrictions within the next few decades, in particular by the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first laws related to abortion were made to protect women from real or perceived risks, and those more restrictive penalized only the provider.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Criminalization did not end the practice of abortion; unlicensed doctors and midwives continued to perform them.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most of the women receiving abortions from unlicensed practitioners were poor.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women's safety continued to be a concern, especially after the highly publicized death of Mary Rogers.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wealthier women could pay willing physicians to broadly interpret health exceptions in their favor.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Euphemistic advertisements for abortifacients offered an assortment of herbal remedies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A number of other factors likely played a role in the rise of anti-abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As in Europe, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century, and the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Physicians, who were the leading advocates of abortion criminalization laws, appear to have been motivated at least in part by advances in medical knowledge.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Science had discovered that fertilization inaugurated a more or less continuous process of development, which produced a new human being.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Quickening was found to be not more or less crucial in the process of gestation than any other step.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many physicians concluded that if society considered it unjustifiable to terminate pregnancy after the fetus had quickened, and if quickening was a relatively unimportant step in the gestation process, then it was just as wrong to terminate a pregnancy before quickening as after quickening.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctors used flawed math to convince the American Medical Association to accept that pre-quickening abortion should also be outlawed, leading to the raft of state laws banning abortion in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doctors were also influenced by practical reasons to advocate anti-abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] For one, abortion providers were usually female midwives without formal training or education.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In an age where the leading doctors in the nation were attempting to standardize the medical profession, these unlicensed practitioners were considered a nuisance to public health.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Despite campaigns to end the practice of abortion, abortifacient advertising was highly effective and abortion was commonly practiced, with the help of a midwife or other women, in the mid-19th century, although they were not always safe.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the precise abortion rate was not known, James Mohr's 1978 book *Abortion in America* documented multiple recorded estimates by 19th-century physicians, which suggested that between around 15% and 35% of all pregnancies ended in abortion during that period.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This era also saw a marked shift in the people who were obtaining abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the start of the 19th century, most abortions were sought by unmarried women, who had become pregnant out of wedlock and for which there was much less compassion compared to married women who got an abortion; many of them were wealthy and paid well.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Out of 54 abortion cases published in American medical journals between 1839 and 1880, over half were sought by married women, and well over 60% of the married women already had at least one child.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The sense that married women were now frequently obtaining abortions worried many conservative physicians, who were almost exclusively men.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Reconstruction era, much of the blame was placed on the burgeoning women's rights movement.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although the medical profession expressed hostility toward feminism, many feminists of the era were also opposed to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Revolution*, a newspaper operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Anthony, an 1869 opinion piece was published arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The writer stated that simply passing an anti-abortion law would be "only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It will burden her conscience in life, it will burden her soul in death; But oh! thrice guilty is he who drove her to the desperation which impelled her to the crime." To many feminists of this era, abortion was regarded as an undesirable necessity forced upon women by thoughtless men.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The free love wing of the feminist movement refused to advocate for abortion and treated the practice as an example of the hideous extremes to which modern marriage was driving women.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Marital rape and the seduction of unmarried women were societal ills, which feminists believed caused the need to abort, as men did not respect women's right to abstinence.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Feminist opposition to abortion was much less prevalent by the 20th century, and it was feminists and physicians who came to question anti-abortion laws and raise public interest in the 1960s.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1873, Anthony Comstock created the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice, an institution dedicated to supervising the morality of the public.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Later that year, Comstock successfully influenced the United States Congress to pass the Comstock Law, which made it illegal to deliver through the U.S. mail any "obscene, lewd, or lascivious" material.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also prohibited producing or publishing information pertaining to the procurement of abortion, birth control, and venereal disease, including to medical students.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The production, publication, importation, and distribution of such materials was suppressed under the Comstock Law as being obscene, and similar prohibitions were passed by 24 of the 37 states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1900, abortion was normally a felony in every state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some states included provisions allowing for abortion in limited circumstances, generally to protect the woman's health or to terminate pregnancies arising from rape or incest.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most Americans did not view abortion as a crime, and abortions continued to occur and became increasingly available.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Birth Control League was founded by Margaret Sanger in 1921; it would become Planned Parenthood Federation of America in 1942.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1930s, licensed physicians performed an estimated 800,000 abortions a year.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1988, 17 year old Becky Bell died from an infection after an unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She lived in Indiana where parental consent was required to have a safe and legal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Tribe wrote in *Abortion: The Clash of Absolutes* that Bell's best friend said that Becky considered an out-of-state abortion to get around Indiana's parental consent requirement.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is possible she performed the abortion herself.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However it was done, Becky died from an infection that was probably caused by the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Her parents publicly campaigned against parental consent laws after her death.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rosie Jimenez died from sepsis in 1977 following an abortion procedure at the home of a midwife who was not licensed to perform abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She did not go to a licensed physician because the Hyde Amendment barring public Medicaid funding for abortions had gone into effect after surviving a statutory challenge in *Beal v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doe* and an Equal Protection challenge in *Maher v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abu Hayat was convicted by a Manhattan Court in 1993 for performing an illegal third trimester abortion at his clinic in Alphabet City.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctor began the dilation and evacuation procedure which was not legal in the third trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The baby was born alive before the procedure could be completed.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She was missing an arm that had been severed during the D&E.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat argued that he was protected from criminal conviction by *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* based on an argument that the baby had not yet been born when he attempted the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Another patient was forced to leave Hayat's clinic halfway through a procedure after Dr.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat demanded more money that her husband could not afford to pay.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The patient nearly died and was treated at a local hospital for severe infection caused by pieces of dismembered fetus being left in her uterus.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 17 year old Sophie McCoy died in 1990 from an infected uterine perforation after receiving an abortion at Dr.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Inequality in access to safe and legal abortions persists to this day whereby many women cannot afford to obtain a legal abortion; in such cases, women may turn to illegal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1960s, a controversy centered around children's television host Sherri Finkbine that helped bring abortion and abortion law more directly into the American public eye.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Living in the area of Phoenix, Arizona, Finkbine had had four healthy children; during her pregnancy with her fifth child, she discovered the child might have severe deformities when born.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was likely because Finkbine had been taking sleeping pills that she was unaware contained thalidomide, a drug that increases the risk of fetal deformities during pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Though Finkbine wanted an abortion, the abortion laws of Arizona only allowed abortions if a pregnancy posed a threat to the woman's life.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The situation gained public attention after Finkbine shared the story with a reporter from *The Arizona Republic*, who disclosed her identity in spite of her requests for anonymity.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On August 18, 1962, Finkbine traveled to Sweden to obtain a legal abortion, where it was confirmed that the fetus had severe deformities.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion, and her photo became the symbol of an abortion-rights movement.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut* struck down one of the remaining contraception Comstock laws in Connecticut and Massachusetts.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, *Griswold* only applied to marital relationships, allowing married couples to buy and use contraceptives without government restriction.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Baird*, to extend the precedent of *Griswold* to unmarried persons as well.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1967, Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were passed in California, Oregon, and North Carolina.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Hawaii became the first state to legalize abortions on the request of the woman, and New York repealed its 1830 law and allowed abortions up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were soon passed in Alaska and Washington.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Washington held a referendum on legalizing early pregnancy abortions, becoming the first state to legalize abortion through a vote of the people.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A law in Washington, D.C., which allowed abortion to protect the life or health of the woman, was challenged in the Supreme Court in 1971 in *United States v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court upheld the law, deeming that "health" meant "psychological and physical well-being", essentially allowing abortion in Washington, D.C.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1972, 13 states had a law similar to that of Colorado, while Mississippi allowed abortion in cases of rape or incest only and Alabama and Massachusetts allowed abortions only in cases where the woman's physical health was endangered.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In order to obtain abortions during this period, women would often travel from a state where abortion was illegal to one where it was legal.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* was that abortion was illegal in 30 states and legal under certain circumstances in 20 states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, 30 states prohibited abortion without exception, 16 states banned abortion except in certain special circumstances (e.g. rape, incest, and health threat to mother), 3 states allowed residents to obtain abortions, and New York allowed abortions generally.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Early that year, on January 22, 1973, the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* invalidated all of these laws, and set guidelines for the availability of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The decision returned abortion to its liberalized pre-1820 status.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* established that the right of privacy of a woman to obtain an abortion "must be considered against important state interests in regulation".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, the Court ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right of privacy in the United States (e.g. federal constitutionally-protected right), in the sense of the right of a person not to be encroached by the state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In its opinion, it listed several landmark cases where the court had previously found a right to privacy implied by the Constitution.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not recognize a right to abortion in all cases, saying: "State regulation protective of fetal life after viability thus has both logical and biological justifications.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A central issue in the *Roe* case and in the wider abortion debate in general is whether human life or personhood begins at conception, birth, or at some point in between.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court declined to make an attempt at resolving this issue, writing: "We need not resolve the difficult question of when life begins.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rather than asserting that human life begins at any specific point, the Court declared that the state has a "compelling interest" in protecting "potential life" at the point of viability.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, state governments may not prohibit late terminations of pregnancy when "necessary to preserve the life or health of the mother", even if it would cause the demise of a viable fetus.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This rule was clarified by the 1973 judicial decision *Doe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton*, which specifies "that the medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is by this provision for the mother's mental health that women in the U.S. legally choose abortion after viability when screenings reveal abnormalities that do not cause a baby to die shortly after birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1966, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops assigned Monsignor James T.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] McHugh to document efforts to reform abortion laws, and anti-abortion groups began forming in various states in 1967.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1968, McHugh led an advisory group which became the National Right to Life Committee.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, in late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1992 case of *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey*, the Court abandoned *Roe's* strict trimester framework but maintained its central holding that women have a right to choose to have an abortion before viability.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* had held that statutes regulating abortion must be subject to "strict scrutiny"—the traditional Supreme Court test for impositions upon fundamental Constitutional rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court continues to make decisions on this subject.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On April 18, 2007, it issued a ruling in the case of *Gonzales v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Carhart*, involving a federal law entitled the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003 which President George W.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The law banned intact dilation and extraction, which opponents of abortion rights referred to as "partial-birth abortion", and stipulated that anyone breaking the law would get a prison sentence up to 2.5 years.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Supreme Court upheld the 2003 ban by a narrow majority of 5–4, marking the first time the Court has allowed a ban on any type of abortion since 1973.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The opinion, which came from justice Anthony Kennedy, was joined by Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and the two recent appointees, Samuel Alito and Chief Justice John Roberts.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hellerstedt*, the Supreme Court in a 5–3 decision on June 27, 2016, swept away forms of state restrictions on the way abortion clinics can function.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court supported this argument and struck down these two provisions "facially" from the law at issue—that is, the very words of the provisions were invalid, no matter how they might be applied in any practical situation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Supreme Court, the task of judging whether a law puts an unconstitutional burden on a woman's right to abortion belongs with the courts, and not the legislatures.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled similarly in *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Russo* on June 29, 2020, in a 5–4 decision that a Louisiana state law, modeled after the Texas law at the center of *Whole Woman's Health*, was unconstitutional.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Like Texas' law, the Louisiana law required certain measures for abortion clinics that, if having gone into effect, would have closed five of the six clinics in the state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case in Louisiana was put on hold pending the result of *Whole Woman's Health*, and was retried based on the Supreme Court's decision.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the District Court ruled the law unconstitutional, the Fifth Circuit found that unlike the Texas law, the burden of the Louisiana law passed the tests outlined in *Whole Woman's Health*, and thus the law was constitutional.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court issued an order to suspend enforcement of the law pending further review, and agreed to hear the case in full in October 2019.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It was the first abortion-related case to be heard by President Donald Trump's appointees to the Court, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court found the Louisiana law unconstitutional for the same reasons as the Texas one, reversing the Fifth Circuit.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The judgment was supported by Chief Justice John Roberts who had dissented on *Whole Woman's Health* but joined in judgment as to upholding the court's respect for the past judgment in that case.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2021, the FDA legalized telemedical provision of abortion pills with delivery by mail, after finding this to be safe and effective, and having suspended enforcement of previous restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June that year, 31 states allowed the practice, fourteen required the prescribing clinician to be physically present, which effectively banned telemedicine, and five explicitly banned telemedical abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court granted *certiorari* to *Dobbs v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* in May 2021, a case that challenges the impact of *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* in blocking enforcement of a 2018 Mississippi law (the Gestational Age Act) that had banned any abortions after the first 15 weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Oral arguments to *Dobbs* were held in December 2021, and a decision was expected by the end of the 2021–22 Supreme Court term.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On September 1, 2021, Texas passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, one of the most restrictive abortion laws in the nation, banning most procedures after six weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 2, 2022, a leaked draft majority opinion for *Dobbs*, written by Samuel Alito, set to overturn *Roe* was reported by *Politico*.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On June 24, 2022, the Supreme Court overruled both *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* in the *Dobbs* case on originalist grounds that a right to abortion cannot be found in the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Roberts, the Chief Justice of the United States, concurred in the decision to uphold the law at question as constitutional, by a 6–3 vote, but did not support overruling both *Roe* and *Casey*.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This enabled trigger laws, which had been passed in 13 states, to ban abortions in those states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Voters in Ohio defeated August 2023 Ohio Issue 1, which intended to make changes to the state's constitution more difficult.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] November 2023 Ohio Issue 1 was then approved by a majority of voters, which added the right to an abortion to the Ohio constitution.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although states nominally allow abortion to prevent the woman's imminent death, five women have died to pregnancy related issues in Texas alone due to doctors refusing to perform abortions because of the state's abortion law despite the *de jure* legal circumstances.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2026, 2024 Nevada Question 6 needs to be approved again to enshrine abortion in the state's constitution, while legislators in Hawaii, Virginia, and the state of Washington proposed similar amendments to codify abortion rights in 2026.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Gerardo Flores was convicted of two counts of capital murder in 2005 under Texas' fetal homicide law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] His girlfriend Erica Basoria testified that she had asked him to step on her stomach because her attempts to induce miscarriage on herself had been unsuccessful.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores said he initially refused but she would not relent until he agreed.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores admitted to police that he "accidentally, probably" hit Basoria in the face during a fight on the night of the miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Basoria told police that he was not abusive.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Texas' fetal homicide law did not allow charges against the mother because she had a right to terminate pregnancy, so only Flores was charged.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019 a woman in Alabama was indicted after she was shot in the stomach for intentionally causing the death of "unborn baby Jones by initiating a fight knowing she was five months pregnant".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Medical abortion via mifepristone and misoprostol was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2007, it was legal and available in all 50 states, Washington, D.C., Guam, and Puerto Rico.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is a prescription drug, but was not initially available to the public through pharmacies; its distribution is primarily restricted to specially qualified licensed physicians, sold by Danco Laboratories under the brand name Mifeprex.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] French pharmaceutical company Roussel-Uclaf, (the company that synthesized mifepristone in 1980 and took it through clinical trials for approval in France by 1988) did not seek US approval, so in the United States legal availability was not initially possible.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States banned importation of mifepristone for personal use in 1989, a decision supported by Roussel Uclaf.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1994, Roussel Uclaf gave the U.S. drug rights to the Population Council in exchange for immunity from any product liability claims.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Population Council sponsored clinical trials in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The drug went on approvable status from 1996.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Production was intended to begin through the Danco Group in 1996, but they withdrew briefly in 1997 due to a corrupt business partner, delaying availability again.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Mifepristone was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved mifepristone, to end a pregnancy through 70 days gestation (70 days or less since the first day of a woman's last menstrual period).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approved dosing regimen is 200 mg of mifepristone taken by mouth (swallowed).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 24 to 48 hours after taking mifepristone, 800 mcg (micrograms) of misoprostol is taken buccally (in the cheek pouch), at a location appropriate for the patient.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of September 2021, in 32 states, the drug could only be provided by a licensed physician, and in 19 states, the prescribing clinician was required to be physically in the room with the patient while they are taking the drug.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic on December 16, 2021, in light of the difficulties in accessing in-person healthcare services, the FDA approved the distribution of mifepristone via mail.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On 16 December 2021, the FDA voluntarily adopted a new rule permanently relaxing the requirement that the pill be obtained in person, allowing it to be sent through the mail.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A prescription is still required, so that a doctor can screen for risk factors that would make taking the pill unsafe for the mother.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the FDA further relaxed rules, allowing any retail pharmacy to become certified to fill mifepristone prescriptions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Department of Justice stated that USPS mailing of pills for medication abortion, even into states where abortion services are restricted, does not violate federal law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2023, online access to abortion medication by mail delivered by the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Postal Service is currently available to citizens of all states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In light of the *Dobbs* decision, the Alliance Defending Freedom launched a lawsuit in November 2022 in the Northern District of Texas under Judge Matthew J.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk to seek to overturn the FDA's original approval of mifepristone.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Judge Kacsmaryk ruled for the Alliance on April 7, 2023, reversing the FDA's approval and banning mifepristone across the United States after seven days.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A district judge in a separate lawsuit, Thomas O.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice of the Eastern District of Washington, ruled that the FDA should not reverse access to mifepristone in 16 states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk's ruling was partially reversed by a panel on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, leaving mifepristone on the market but reverting efforts made by the FDA to liberalize its use over seven years.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case was appealed to the Supreme Court, and on June 13, 2024, the court ruled that the Alliance Defending Freedom lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, GenBioPro filed suit to overturn state laws that prohibit sale of mifepristone, claiming that such laws are invalid because it is a federally approved drug.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The argument that state laws seeking to ban or restrict the use of mifepristone are preempted by the FDA's decision to make the drug available is supported by a number of Supreme Court decisions, including opinions by the traditionally more conservative Justices.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In March 2023, Wyoming became the first US state to ban the pill.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In April 2023, in a lawsuit brought by 17 US states and the District of Columbia, federal district judge Thomas O.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice issued a temporary injunction that the FDA should not reduce access to mifepristone in these states and the district.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In May 2024, the state of Louisiana classified mifepristone and misoprostol as controlled substances, with penalties for possession without a prescription.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The move follows concerns over coerced abortion and has drawn criticism from over 240 doctors in the state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2025, the states of Florida and Texas filed a lawsuit against the FDA challenging its approval of mifepristone in 2000 and approval of a generic in 2025.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After regulations on abortion early in pregnancy were ruled constitutional by the 2022 decision *Dobbs v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, some states enacted restrictions on abortions and abortion pills.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the United States Department of Justice issued an interpretation of the Comstock Act that it was legal for United States Postal Service employees to deliver the pills in any state, because they could not know whether the pills would be used for an abortion or other purposes.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine* lawsuit, federal district judge Matthew J.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk issued a preliminary injunction suspending the 2000 approval of mifepristone, which would take effect a week later.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fifth Circuit reversed parts of Kacsmaryk's injunction, but placed a temporary injunction on the 2016 REMS change to mifepristone.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On appeal to the Supreme Court, the Court stayed both injunctions on 21 April 2023, with only Justices Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas stating their dissent.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The stay allowed mifepristone to remain legally available while the lower courts consider the merits of the case.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In June 2024, the US Supreme Court unanimously overturned judge Kacsmaryk's Fifth Circuit decision on the grounds that the Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine had no standing to challenge the FDA's regulations of mifepristone.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled that Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine did not demonstrate that they would suffer harm to warrant standing.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not rule on the substance of mifepristone, abortion, or the FDA's procedures.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some drugs are approved by the FDA under subsection H, which has two subparts.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first sets forth ways to rush experimental drugs, such as aggressive HIV and cancer treatments, to market when speedy approval is deemed vital to the health of potential patients.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The second part of subsection H applies to drugs that not only must meet restrictions for use due to safety requirements, but also are required to meet postmarketing surveillance to establish that the safety results shown in clinical trials are seconded by use in a much wider population.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Until December 2021, Mifepristone was approved under the second part of subsection H.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The result is that women could not pick the drug up at a pharmacy, but were required to receive it directly from a doctor.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approval of mifepristone under subsection H included a black box warning.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] During the COVID pandemic, and coupled with growing restrictions on abortion access in conservative states, the FDA performed trial runs of telemedical abortions, allowing doctors to prescribe mifepristone and other medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit by the patient.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By December 2021, the FDA advanced approval to for telemedical abortions for all registered providers. which was made final by 2023.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of July 2025, 25 states allowed telemedical abortions, the prescription of medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit to a doctor, without restriction, 13 states allowed abortion but had restrictions on telemedical abortions, and 12 states banned abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The FDA's action, coupled with the *Dobbs* decision, led many conservative states to seek new laws to ban citizens in their states from telemedical abortion, or seeking penalties from those that prescribe that medication from other states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As a result, eight states where telemedical abortion was legal passed shield laws shield laws to enable physicians to remotely prescribe abortion medication to patients in states where abortion is banned.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In October 2025, Louisiana Attorney General Liz Murrill and the Alliance Defending Freedom filed Louisiana v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] FDA against the Food and Drug Administration and Department of Health and Human Services challenging the 2023 Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) for mifepristone which removed the in-person dispensing requirement.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republican Attorneys General of 21 states filed in support of Louisiana's lawsuit.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The lawsuit is one of several brought by Republican Attorneys General seeking to restrict mifepristone.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Joseph paused the case while the second Trump administration conducts a review of the 2023 REMS.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 1, 2026, Republican-appointed Judges Kyle Duncan, Leslie H.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Engelhardt on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals unanimously blocked the 2023 REMS, preventing the mailing of mifepristone country-wide.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, the Supreme Court temporarily lifted the Fifth Circuit's order via the shadow docket on May 4, and stayed it for an indefinite period on May 14, over dissent from Alito and Thomas.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The ruling will remain in effect through at least the course of the Louisiana-FDA lawsuit, which is expected to continue into the year 2027.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Beyond limitations pertaining to abortion in the context of federal funding, there is little federal legislation protecting or penalizing abortion in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003, Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act of 1994, and Comstock Act of 1873 are some of the few pieces of existing federal law that provide substantive criminal provisions either protecting or penalizing abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions in the Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act and the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act cover activity affecting interstate or foreign commerce, to which the former was upheld (against constitutional attack under the 5th amendment) by the Supreme Court in *Gonzales v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions of the Comstock Act primarily cover activity using the mail or postal system, and the Comstock Act was first upheld by Supreme Court in *Ex parte Jackson* (1878).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The legality of abortion is frequently a major issue in nomination battles for the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Nominees typically remain silent on the issue during their hearings, as the issue may come before them as judges.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2021, the Women's Health Protection Act, which would protect abortion rights by federal statute, was introduced by Judy Chu.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] House of Representatives but was rejected by the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] After the *Dobbs* decision, Merrick Garland, then-U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Attorney General, asserted that under federal law, states do not have the power to restrict access to FDA-approved abortion pills.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Currently, 13 states have criminal penalties for performing abortions, regardless of gestational age.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The penalties in states that have made abortion illegal vary, as outlined below.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This chart lists only the penalties authorized specifically by the state laws which explicitly restrict (or ban) abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The chart does not address the risk of being prosecuted for violating any other law because of the abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] States with criminal penalties that are blocked by a court or have yet to take effect are denoted by a gray background.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Prior to 2021, abortion was legal in all U.S. states, and every state had at least one abortion clinic.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion is a controversial political issue, and regular attempts to restrict it occur in most states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Two such cases, originating in Texas and Louisiana, led to the Supreme Court cases of *Whole Woman's Health v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Hellerstedt* (2016) and *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Russo* (2020) in which several Texas and Louisiana restrictions were struck down.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The issue of minors and abortion is regulated at the state level, and 37 states require some parental involvement, either in the form of parental consent or in the form of parental notification.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In certain situations, the parental restrictions can be overridden by a court.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Mandatory waiting periods, mandatory ultrasounds and scripted counseling are common abortion regulations.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion laws are generally stricter in conservative Southern states than they are in other parts of the country.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, New York passed the Reproductive Health Act (RHA), which repealed a pre-*Roe* provision that banned third-trimester abortions except in cases where the continuation of the pregnancy endangered a pregnant woman's life.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion in the Northern Mariana Islands, a United States Commonwealth territory, is illegal.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Alabama House Republicans passed a law on April 30, 2019, that will criminalize most abortion if it goes into effect.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Dubbed the "Human Life Protection Act", it offers only two exceptions: serious health risk to the mother or a lethal fetal anomaly.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amendments that would have added cases of rape or incest to the list of exceptions were rejected It will also make the procedure a Class A felony.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Twenty-five male Alabama senators voted to pass the law on May 13.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The next day, Alabama governor Kay Ivey signed the bill into law, primarily as a symbolic gesture in hopes of challenging *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since Alabama introduced the first modern anti-abortion legislation in April 2019, five other states have also adopted abortion laws including Mississippi, Kentucky, Ohio, Georgia and most recently Louisiana on May 30, 2019.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court upheld an Indiana state law that requires fetuses which were aborted be buried or cremated.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In a December 2019 case, the court declined to review a lower court decision which upheld a Kentucky law requiring doctors to perform ultrasounds and show fetal images to patients before abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On June 29, 2020, previous Supreme Court rulings banning abortion restrictions appeared to be upheld when the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court struck down the Louisiana anti-abortion law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Following the ruling, the legality of laws restricting abortion in states such as Ohio was then called into question.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It was also noted that Supreme Court Chief Justice John Roberts, who agreed that the Louisiana anti-abortion law was unconstitutional, had previously voted to uphold a similar law in Texas which was struck down by the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In order to avoid traditional constitutional challenges based on *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Plaintiffs sought an order from the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court to stop the law from coming into effect, but the Court issued a denial of the order late on September 1, 2021, allowing the law to remain in effect.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While unsigned, Chief Justice John Roberts and Justice Stephen Breyer wrote dissenting opinions joined by Justices Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor that they would have granted an injunction on the law until a proper judicial review.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Garland further noted that the United States government has "an obligation to ensure that no state can deprive individuals of their constitutional rights." The Complaint avers that Texas enacted the law "in open defiance of the Constitution".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] District Court in Austin, Texas includes a declaration that the Texas Act is unconstitutional, and an injunction against state actors as well as any and all private individuals who may bring a SB 8 action.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The idea of asking a federal court to impose an injunction upon the entire civilian population of a state is unprecedented and has drawn eyebrows.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In April 2022 Colorado passed into law its Reproductive Health Equity Act, which assures abortion rights for all citizens of the state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On May 25, 2022, Oklahoma imposed a ban on almost all abortions after Oklahoma Governor Kevin Stitt signed House Bill 4327.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill bans abortion beginning at conception, with exceptions only in cases of "rape, sexual assault, or incest that has been reported to law enforcement", or if "the abortion is necessary to save the life of a pregnant woman in a medical emergency".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law also permits private citizens to file lawsuits against (1) abortion providers (2) any individual who "aids and abets" an induced abortion, including paying for an abortion through insurance or otherwise, or (3) any individuals who *intend* to provide or to aid and abet an induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A lawsuit was immediately filed by the ACLU in opposition to the bill.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] At the time of enactment, Oklahoma was the only U.S. state to have passed a bill imposing such restrictions; the law made Oklahoma the first U.S. state to ban induced abortion procedures since prior to the ruling and implementation of *Roe* in 1973.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] on June 24, 2022, after the Supreme Court overturned *Roe*, Texas and Missouri immediately banned abortions with the exception only if the pregnancy was deemed to be particularly life-threatening.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 28, 2023, the Minnesota state Senate passed a bill guaranteeing women's rights to abortion and other reproductive medicine which was signed into law on January 31.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill prohibits state and local governments from attempting to restrict access to sterilization or prenatal care, while also requiring contraceptive cost compensation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2024 abortion in Iowa was made illegal after 6 weeks of gestation, with exceptions for rape, incest, foetal abnormalities, and the mother's life.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, five women launched a class action lawsuit against the State of Texas after they were reportedly denied abortions at a clinic in the State despite grave risks to their life.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Four of the women traveled out of state in order to obtain an abortion, while the fifth only received the abortion in Texas when she was hospitalized after the fetus suffered a premature rupture of membranes.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The case argues that the Texas law, which allows abortion if there is a health risk to the mother, is too vague and doctors will not perform an abortion for fear of legal repercussions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amid the COVID-19 pandemic, anti-abortion government officials in several American states enacted or attempted to enact restrictions on abortion, characterizing it as a non-essential procedure that can be suspended during the medical emergency.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The orders have led to several legal challenges and criticism by human rights groups and several national medical organizations, including the American Medical Association.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Legal challenges on behalf of abortion providers, many of which were represented by the American Civil Liberties Union and Planned Parenthood, successfully stopped most of the orders on a temporary basis.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] One challenge was made against the FDA's rule on the distribution of mifepristone (RU-486), one of the two-part drug regimen to induce abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2000, it is only available through health providers under the FDA's ruling.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, access to mifepristone was a concern, and the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists along with other groups sued to have the rule relaxed to allow women to be able to access mifepristone at home through mail-order or retail pharmacies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While the Fourth Circuit issued a preliminary injunction against the FDA's ruling that would have allowed wider distribution, the Supreme Court ordered in a 6–3 decision in January 2021 to put a stay on the injunction, maintaining the FDA's rule.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2019, the anti-abortion movement in the United States has sought declarations of "sanctuary cit[ies] for the unborn".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2019, the city council of Waskom, Texas, voted to outlaw abortion in the city, declaring Waskom a "sanctuary city for the unborn" (the first such city to designate itself as such), as state governments elsewhere in the United States were also drafting abortion bans.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As of July 2019, there is no abortion clinic in the city.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Waskom ordinance has led other small cities in Texas, and as of April 2021 in Nebraska, to vote in favor of becoming "sanctuary cities for the unborn".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On April 6, 2021, Hayes Center, Nebraska, became the first city in Nebraska to outlaw abortion by local ordinance, declaring itself a "sanctuary city for the unborn." The city of Blue Hill, Nebraska, followed suit and enacted a similar ordinance outlawing abortion on April 13, 2021.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In May 2021, Lubbock, Texas, with a population of less than 270,000, voted to ban abortion with the "sanctuary city for the unborn ordinance", becoming the largest city in the U.S. to ban abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rights movements have also pushed for similar counterpart legislation in other cities.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The abortion debate has also been extended to the question of who pays the medical costs of the procedure, with some states using the mechanism as a way of reducing the number of abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The cost of an abortion varies depending on factors such as location, facility, timing, type of procedure, and whether or not there is insurance or some other type of financial assistance.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2022, a medication abortion cost was about $580 at Planned Parenthood, though it could be more, up to around $800, in other facilities.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first trimester an in-clinic abortion cost up to around $800, though often less; the average cost at Planned Parenthood was about $600.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A second trimester procedure varied depending on the stage of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The average ranged from about $715 earlier in the second trimester to $1,500–2,000 later in the second trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of resources from support organizations are available to contribute to the costs of the procedure, as well as travel expenses.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of organizations offer financial support for people seeking abortions, including travel and other expenses.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Access Reproductive Care–Southeast (ARC Southeast), the Brigid Alliance, the Midwest Access Coalition (MAC), and the National Network of Abortion Funds are examples of such groups.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Hyde Amendment is a federal legislative provision barring the use of federal Medicaid funds to pay for abortions except for rape and incest.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provision, in various forms, was in response to *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*, and has been routinely attached to annual appropriations bills since 1976, and represented the first major legislative success by the pro-life movement.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law requires that states cover abortions under Medicaid in the event of rape, incest, and life endangerment.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Under this policy, U.S. federal funding to NGOs that provide abortion is not permitted.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was first announced by President Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It has been rescinded by Democratic presidents and reinstated by Republican presidents.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was rescinded in 2021 by President Joe Biden and reinstated on January 24, 2025, by President Donald Trump.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Qualifying requirements for performing abortions vary from state to state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Vermont has allowed physician assistants to do some first-trimester abortions since the mid-1970s.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] More recently, several states have changed their requirements for abortion providers, anticipating that the Supreme Court would overturn *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*; now that the court has done so, more states are expanding eligibility to provide abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other states, non-physicians are not permitted to perform abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Because reporting of abortions is not mandatory, statistics are of varying reliability.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Both the Centers For Disease Control (CDC) and the Guttmacher Institute regularly compile these statistics.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] However, in 2024 the Guttmacher Institute raised alarm that the Trump administration has severely gutted CDC efforts to collect these data.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The annual number of legal induced abortions in the U.S. doubled between 1973 and 1979, and peaked in 1990.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There was a slow but steady decline throughout the 1990s.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Overall, the number of annual abortions decreased by 6% between 2000 and 2009, with temporary spikes in 2002 and 2006.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2011, abortion rate in the nation dropped to its lowest point since the Supreme Court legalized the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to a study performed by Guttmacher Institute, long-acting contraceptive methods had a significant impact in reducing unwanted pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There were fewer than 17 abortions for every 1,000 women of child-bearing age.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] That was a 13%-decrease from 2008's numbers and slightly higher than the rate in 1973, when the Supreme Court's *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The study indicated a long-term decline in the abortion rate.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2016, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported 623,471 abortions, a 2% decrease from 636,902 in 2015.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first six months of 2023 (following *Dobbs* in 2022), the numbers of abortions in certain U.S. states changed dramatically compared to the same time period in 2020, according to the Guttmacher Institute.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortions tripled in New Mexico and Wyoming and more than doubled in South Carolina and Kansas.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For 13 states that had banned abortion, the Guttmacher Institute had no 2023 data to make the comparison.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A Guttmacher Institute survey of abortion providers estimated that early medical abortions accounted for 17% of all non-hospital abortions and slightly over one-quarter of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in the United States in 2008.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Medical abortions accounted for 32% of first-trimester abortions at Planned Parenthood clinics in 2008.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2020, medication abortions accounted for more than 50% of all abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, medication abortions obtained within the formal health care system had risen to 63% of all abortions, with the total percentage (which would include self-managed abortions by individuals in states with total bans) likely higher.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of abortions are obtained by religiously identified women.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Guttmacher Institute, "more than 7 in 10 U.S. women obtaining an abortion report a religious affiliation (37% Protestant, 28% Catholic, and 7% other), and 25% attend religious services at least once a month.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rates tend to be higher among minority women in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000–2001, the rates among black and Hispanic women were 49 per 1,000 and 33 per 1,000, respectively, vs.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] 13 per 1,000 among non-Hispanic white women.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This figure includes all women of reproductive age, including women that are not pregnant.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other words, these abortion rates reflect the rate at which U.S. women of reproductive age have an abortion each year.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2004, the rates of abortion by ethnicity in the U.S. were 50 abortions per 1,000 black women, 28 abortions per 1,000 Hispanic women, and 11 abortions per 1,000 white women.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade legalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1972, 41% of abortions were performed on women outside their state of residence, while in 1973 it declined to 21%, and then to 11% in 1974.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In the decade from 2011 to 2020, during which many states increased abortion restrictions, the percentage of women nationwide who traveled out of state for an abortion increased steadily, from 6% in 2011 to 9% in 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Out of state travel for an abortion was much more prevalent in the 29 states hostile to abortion rights, with percentages in those states rising from 9% in 2011 to 15% by 2020, while in states supportive of abortion rights, out of state travel for abortions rose from 2% to 3% between 2011 and 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2024, around 155,000 people crossed state lines for abortions, doubling the number in 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In several states the percentage of abortions performed within the state specifically for people who traveled from outside of the state exceeds 15%, with Kansas, New Mexico, and Washington DC exceeding 50%.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Illinois performed the most out-of-state abortions in the US at 23% or 34,900 cases.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, from 2017 to 2020, the *abortion rate by state of residence* for Missourians went up by 18% from 8.4 to 9.9.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Some out of state travel pertains to locations of population centers in states; if large cities are close to state borders it may be common to cross borders for an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Delaware, which is generally supportive of abortion rights, saw 44% of residents obtain their abortions in neighboring states.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The source of this information takes findings into account from 27 nations including the United States, and therefore, these findings may not be typical for any one nation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000, cases of rape or incest accounted for 1% of abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A 2008 National Survey of Family Growth (NSFG) shows that rates of unintended pregnancy are highest among Blacks, Hispanics, and women with lower socio-economic status.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control, in 2011, most (64.5%) abortions were performed by ≤8 weeks' gestation, and nearly all (91.4%) were performed by ≤13 weeks' gestation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Few abortions (7.3%) were performed between 14 and 20 weeks' gestation or at ≥21 weeks' gestation (1.4%).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] From 2002 to 2011, the percentage of all abortions performed at ≤8 weeks' gestation increased 6%.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of death from carrying a child to term in the U.S. is approximately 14 times greater than the risk of death from a legal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2012, the mortality rate from legal abortion was 0.6 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth through at least 21 weeks' gestation.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For the period 2013 – 2019, the rate of mortality from legal abortion procedures in the US was 0.43 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 reported legal abortions, lower than the rates for previous 5-year periods.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, there were four identified deaths related to abortion in the US, out of 625,000 abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As an element of family planning, birth control was federally subsidized for low income families in 1965 under President Lyndon B.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1970, Congress passed Title X to provide family planning services for those in need, and President Richard Nixon signed it into law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Funding for Title X rose from $6 million in 1971 to $61 million the next year, and slowly increased each year to $317 million in 2010, after which it was reduced by a few percent.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2011, the Guttmacher Institute reported that the number of abortions in the U.S. would be nearly two-thirds higher without access to birth control.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2015, the Federation of American Scientists reported that federally mandated access to birth control had helped reduce teenage pregnancies in the U.S. by 44 percent, and had prevented more than 188,000 unintended pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The level of support for access to abortion has been relatively consistent since 1972.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Large majorities (over 75%) support access to abortion in "traumatic" cases (rape, danger to the mother's health, or strong chance of birth defects) and approximately 40-50% support elective abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Americans have been equally divided on the issue; a May 2018 Gallup poll indicated that 48% of Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" and 48% described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A July 2018 poll indicated that 64% of Americans did not want the Supreme Court to overturn *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that support for abortion being generally legal was 60% during the first trimester of pregnancy, dropping to 28% in the second trimester, and 13% in the third trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In January 2013, a majority of Americans believed abortion should be legal in all or most cases, according to a poll by NBC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Approximately 70% of respondents in the same poll opposed *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A poll by the Pew Research Center yielded similar results.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Moreover, 48% of Republicans opposed overturning *Roe*, compared to 46% who supported overturning it.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup declared in May 2010 that more Americans identifying as "pro-life" is "the new normal", while also noting that there had been no increase in opposition to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] It suggested that political polarization may have prompted more Republicans to call themselves "pro-life".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The terms "pro-choice" and "pro-life" do not always reflect a political view or fall along a binary; in one Public Religion Research Institute poll, seven in ten Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" while almost two-thirds described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that 56% of Americans were in favor of legal access to abortion in all or some cases.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 90% approve of abortion when the health of the woman is endangered, 77.4% when there is a strong chance of defects in the baby that could result from the pregnancy, and 79.5% when the pregnancy is the result of rape.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A 2022 poll by the Pew Research Center, found that 47% polled said that women who had an illegal abortion should face a penalty.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 14% said they should face jail time, 16% said a fine or community services and 17% were not sure the penalty.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade and significantly reduced access to abortion, dissatisfaction with the country's abortion policies rose to 69% (the highest level in 23 years), of which 46% want fewer restrictions on abortion, a significant increase from previous years.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since then, a consistent majority of the public has identified as pro-choice, with 52% identifying as pro-choice and 44% as pro-life in May 2023.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Pew Research Center polling shows little change in views from 2008 to 2012; modest differences based on gender or age.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The original article's table also shows by party affiliation, religion, and education level.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Support for the legalization of abortion is significantly higher among more educated adults than less educated, and has been consistently so for decades.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2019, 70% of college graduates support abortion being legal in all or most cases, as well as 60% of those with some college education, compared to 54% of those with a high school degree or less.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2003 CBS News/*The New York Times* poll examined whether Americans thought abortion should be legal or not, and found variations in opinion which depended upon party affiliation and the region of the country.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The margin of error is +/– 4% for questions answered of the entire sample (overall figures) and may be higher for questions asked of subgroups (all other figures).
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2026 poll by Pew Research found that support for legal abortion in the U.S. varies by race.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Polls indicates general support of legal abortion during the first trimester, although support drops dramatically for abortion during the second and third trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since the 2011 poll, support for legal abortion during the first trimester has declined.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to Gallup's long-time polling on abortion, the majority of Americans are neither strictly "pro-life" or "pro-choice"; it depends upon the circumstances of the pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup polling from 1996 to 2021 consistently reveals that when asked the question, "Do you think abortions should be legal under any circumstances, legal only under certain circumstances, or illegal in all circumstances?", Americans repeatedly answer "legal only under certain circumstances".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the poll, in any given year 48–57% say legal only under certain circumstances, 21–34% say legal under any circumstances, and 13–19% illegal in all circumstances, with 1–7% having no opinion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the aforementioned poll, Americans differ drastically based upon situation of the pregnancy, suggesting they do not support unconditional abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Congress outlawed intact dilation and extraction when it passed the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A Rasmussen Reports poll four days after the Supreme Court's opinion in *Gonzales v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Carhart* found that 40% of respondents "knew the ruling allowed states to place some restrictions on specific abortion procedures." Of those who knew of the decision, 56% agreed with the decision and 32% were opposed.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] An ABC poll from 2003 found that 62% of respondents thought "partial-birth abortion" should be illegal; a similar number of respondents wanted an exception "if it would prevent a serious threat to the woman's health".
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup has repeatedly queried the American public on this issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] After *Roe*, there was a national political realignment surrounding abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement in the United States initially emphasized the national policy benefits of abortion, such as smaller welfare expenses, slower population growth, and fewer illegitimate births.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement drew support from the population control movement, feminists, and environmentalists.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Anti-abortion advocates and civil-rights activists accused abortion-rights supporters of intending to control the population of racial minorities and the disabled, citing their ties to racial segregationists and eugenicist legal reformers.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement subsequently distanced from the population control movement, and responded by taking up choice-based and rights-oriented rhetoric similar to what was used in the *Roe* decision.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Opponents of abortion experienced a political shift.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Catholic Church and the Democratic Party supported an expansive welfare state, wanted to reduce rates of abortion through prenatal insurance and federally funded day care, and opposed abortion at the time of *Roe*.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Afterwards, the anti-abortion movement in the United States shifted more to Protestant faiths that saw abortion rights as part of a liberal-heavy agenda to fight against, and became part of the new Christian right.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Protestant influence helped make opposition to abortion part of the Republican Party's platform by the 1990s.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republican-led states enacted laws to restrict abortion, including abortions earlier than *Casey*'s general standard of 24 weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Into the 21st century, although members of both major U.S. political parties come down on either side of the issue, the Republican Party is often seen as being anti-abortion, since the official party platform opposes abortion and considers fetuses to have an inherent right to life.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republicans for Choice represents the minority of that party.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 9% of Republicans favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Republican National Convention delegates in 2004, 13% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 17% of all Republican voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Democratic Party platform considers abortion to be a woman's right.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Democrats for Life of America represents the minority of that party.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 74% of Democrats favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Democratic National Convention delegates in 2004, 75% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 2% believed that abortion should not be permitted.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 49% of all Democratic voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 13% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The position of U.S. third political parties and other U.S. minor political parties is diverse.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Green Party supports legal abortion as a woman's right.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Constitution Party is opposed to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The issue of abortion has become deeply politicized.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2002, 84% of state Democratic platforms supported the right to having an abortion while 88% of state Republican platforms opposed it.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] This divergence also led to Christian right organizations like Christian Voice, Christian Coalition of America, and Moral Majority having an increasingly strong role in the Republican Party.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The policy was revoked by President Bill Clinton and subsequently reinstated by President George W.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Barack Obama overruled this policy by Executive Order on January 23, 2009, and it was reinstated on January 23, 2017, by President Donald Trump.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On January 28, 2021, President Joe Biden signed a Presidential Memorandum that repealed the restoration of Mexico City policy and also called for the United States Department of Health and Human Services to "suspend, rescind or revoke" restrictions made to Title X.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Donald Trump reinstated the policy on January 24, 2025.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The risk of death due to legal abortion has fallen considerably since *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade* (1973) legalized it; this was due to increased physician skills, improved medical technology, and earlier termination of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] From 1940 through 1970, annual deaths of pregnant women during abortion fell from nearly 1,500 to a little over 100.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the number of women who died in 1972 from illegal abortion was thirty-nine.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Roe effect is a hypothesis suggesting that since supporters of abortion rights cause the erosion of their own political base by having fewer children, the practice of abortion will eventually lead to the restriction or illegalization of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The legalized abortion and crime effect is another controversial theory that posits legal abortion reduces crime because unwanted children are more likely to become criminals.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since *Roe*, there have been numerous attempts to reverse the decision.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the 2011 election season, Mississippi placed an amendment on the ballot that redefined how the state viewed abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The personhood amendment defined personhood as "every human being from the moment of fertilization, cloning or the functional equivalent thereof"; if passed, it would have been illegal to get an abortion in the state.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On July 11, 2012, a Mississippi federal judge ordered an extension of his temporary order to allow the state's only abortion clinic to stay open.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The order was to stay in place until U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] District Judge Daniel Porter Jordan III could review newly drafted rules on how the Mississippi Department of Health would administer a new abortion law.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The law in question came into effect on July 1, 2012.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Between 2008 and 2016, the Turnaway Study followed a group of 1,000 women, two of whom died after giving birth, for five years after they sought an abortion, and compared their health and socio-economic consequences of receiving an abortion or being denied one.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The study found that those who were provided with abortion performed better, and those who were denied one suffered negative consequences.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] *Scientific American* described it as landmark.
[src:abortion-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A follow-up Turnaway Study was confirmed to determinate the health and economic impact of *Roe* being overturned, which other scholars also analyzed.
